{"title_page": "Manhattan Municipal Building", "text_new": "{{Short description|Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name =Manhattan Municipal Building\n| nrhp_type =\n| image =Municipal Building - New York City.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption =\n| location= [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| locmapin = Lower Manhattan#New York City#New York#USA\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|42|46.67|N|74|0|13.99|W|display=inline,title}}\n| area =\n| built =1907\u20131914<ref name=aia4 /><ref name=nycland />\n| architect= [[William M. Kendall]]\n| architecture = [[Ancient Roman architecture|Ancient Roman]]<br />[[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]]<br />[[French Renaissance architecture|French Renaissance]]<br />[[Renaissance architecture|Renaissance]]\n| added = October 18, 1972\n| governing_body = City of New York\n| refnum=72000879<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2006a}}</ref>\n| designated_other2_name = NYC Landmark\n| designated_other2_date = February 1, 1966\n| designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n| designated_other2_link = New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission\n| designated_other2_number =\n| designated_other2_color = #ffe978\n}}\n\nThe '''David N. Dinkins Municipal Building''', originally the '''Municipal Building''' and then the '''Manhattan Municipal Building''',<ref>[http://www.nyc-architecture.com/SCC/SCC030.htm The Municipal Building], ''New York Architecture''.</ref> is a 40-story, {{Convert|580|ft|m|abbr=|adj=on}} building at 1 [[Centre Street (Manhattan)|Centre Street]] in [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], near the intersection with [[Chambers Street (Manhattan)|Chambers Street]]. The structure was built to accommodate increased governmental space demands after the [[City of Greater New York|1898 consolidation]] of the city's [[Borough (New York City)|five boroughs]], with construction beginning in 1907 and continuing through 1914.<ref name=\"aia4\">{{cite AIA4|page=71}}</ref><ref name=\"nycland\">{{cite nycland|page=33}}</ref>\n\nThe Manhattan Municipal Building's construction marked the end of the [[City Beautiful movement]] in New York. [[William M. Kendall]]<ref name=\"aia4\" /> of the noted [[architectural firm]] [[McKim, Mead & White]] designed the building, which was the first to incorporate a [[New York City Subway|subway]] station \u2013 the [[Chambers Street (BMT Nassau Street Line)|Chambers Street]] station, served by the {{NYCS trains|Nassau north}} \u2013 into its base. Enormously influential in the civic construction of other American cities, the building's [[architectural style]] has been \"variously described as [[Ancient Roman architecture|Roman Imperial]], [[Renaissance architecture|Italian Renaissance]], [[French Renaissance architecture|French Renaissance]], or [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]].\"<ref>Sarah Bradford Landau & Carl W. Condit, ''Rise of the New York Skyscraper: 1865\u20131913'' (Yale University Press, 1999), p. 374.</ref>\n\nThe Municipal Building is one of the largest governmental buildings in the world. At present, the Municipal Building is home to \"over 2,000 employees from a dozen municipal agencies in nearly 1 million square feet of office space.\"<ref name=\"NYDCAS\">[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcas/html/about/man_munibldg.shtml Manhattan Municipal Building], [[New York City Department of Citywide Administrative Services]] (accessed September 27, 2015).</ref>\n\n__TOC__\n\n==History==\n\n=== Planning and construction ===\n{{multiple image\n| align     = left\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1    = Municipal Building New York.jpg\n| width1    = 169\n| caption1  = Under construction, {{circa|1912}}\n| image2    = Colin Campbell Cooper, Chambers Street and the Municipal Building, N.Y.C.jpg\n| width2    = 180\n| caption2  = ''Chambers Street and the Municipal Building'' by [[Colin Campbell Cooper]], c. 1922\n}}\n\nIn the 1884 annual report of the City of New York, Mayor [[Franklin Edson]] declared that more space was badly needed for governmental functions. But he also noted that [[New York City Hall|City Hall]] was not expandable because its \"style of architecture was such that without marring its present symmetry, it couldn't be enlarged to the required extent.\"\n\nThe City's agencies rented space in various buildings strewn all the way from [[Downtown Manhattan]] up to [[Midtown Manhattan]], with the number of such arrangements increasing by the year. The government, desiring to cut down the amount of rent paid to private landlords, held several design competitions for a new, massive building that would be suitable to house many agencies under one roof. Mayor [[Abram Hewitt]] appointed a commission to study suitable plans and plots of land in 1888, and four competitions were held between that year and 1907.  The final competition was held by the Commissioner of Bridges, who had already secured a new plot of land to be used for a new [[tram|trolley]] hub at the Manhattan base of [[Brooklyn Bridge]]. Twelve architectural firms entered the last competition, and the winning entry was received from [[William Mitchell Kendall]],<ref name=encnyc2 /> a young partner of [[McKim, Mead & White]], which had been urged to enter the contest by Mayor [[George B. McClellan, Jr.]]<ref name=encnyc2>Willis, Carol. \"Municipal Building\" in {{cite enc-nyc2|pages=863\u2013864}}</ref> McKim, Mead was at the time the largest architectural firm in the world, with a staff numbering over 100. Despite their standing in the architectural community, the Manhattan Municipal Building would be their first [[skyscraper]].\n\nThe building was first occupied in January 1913, and the majority of the building's offices were opened to the public by 1916.\n\n=== Later use ===\n{{Expand section|date=November 2019}}\nThe facade of the building was restored in 1990 by the architects [[Wank Adams Slavin]].<ref name=\"aia4\" />\n\nThe building was designated a [[List of New York City Landmarks|New York City landmark]] in 1966,<ref name=\"nycland\" /> and was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1972.  On October 14, 2015, the building was renamed after former mayor [[David N. Dinkins]].<ref>Ngo, Emily. [http://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/nyc-municipal-building-renamed-for-former-mayor-david-n-dinkins-1.10967492 \"NYC Municipal Building renamed for former Mayor Dinkins\"] ''[[Newsday]]'' (October 15, 2015)</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Art and architecture==\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1    = 2008-05-04 CanonS3 IMG 3076 Civic Fame crop.jpg\n | width1    = 136\n | caption1   = The gilded statue of ''Civic Fame'' at the top\n | image2    = Manhattan Municipal Building 3034848677 a09e975842b.jpg\n | width2    = 163\n | caption2  = [[Guastavino tile|Guastavino ceiling tiles]] on the south arcade\n | image3    = Municipal Building Arch.jpg\n | width3    = 150\n | caption3  = The central arch, inspired by the Roman [[Arch of Constantine]]\n}}\nThe building features various types of sculpture and relief.<ref name=\"NYDCAS\"/> The [[New York City Department of Citywide Administrative Services]] reports:\n\n{{quote|The central arch is decorated with [[Neoclassical architecture|sculpture in the Roman manner]] as was used in the [[Arch of Constantine]]. Over the side arches are rectangular allegorical panels. At the left (north), ''Civic Duty'' is represented by a woman personifying the City, accompanied by a child holding the seal of the city. On the right of the arch (south), ''Civic Pride'' shows the female personification of the city receiving tribute from her citizens. Adolph Weinman, the sculptor of ''Civic Fame'', also designed the shields that were used in the elevators, on the molding above the colonnade and again on the false colonnade above the 22nd floor. They represent [[New Amsterdam]], the [[Province of New York]] (under English rule), the City of New York, the [[County of New York]] and the State of New York.<ref name=\"NYDCAS\"/>}}\n\nThe central arch is large enough that automobile traffic once went through it. However, in modern times, [[Chambers Street (Manhattan)|Chambers Street]] has been shortened and no longer continues east through the arch. A screen of [[Corinthian column]]s flanks the arch.<ref name=nycland />\n\nThe [[terra-cotta]] [[vault (architecture)|vault]] was modeled on the entrance of the [[Palazzo Farnese]] in [[Rome]], and the south arcade has a ceiling of white [[Guastavino tile]]s.<ref name=nycland />\n\n===''Civic Fame''===\nAt the top of the Municipal Building is the statue ''Civic Fame'', installed in March 1913. The statue is a [[Gilding|gilded]] [[copper]] figure, made from about 500 pieces of hammered copper.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\">[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcas/html/about/civicfame.shtml Civic Fame] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304200909/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcas/html/about/civicfame.shtml |date=March 4, 2016 }}, [[New York City Department of Citywide Administrative Services]] (accessed September 27, 2015).</ref><ref name=\"Artwalks\">Marina Harrison & Lucy D. Rosenfeld, ''Artwalks in New York: Delightful Discoveries of Public Art and Gardens in Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens, the Bronx, and Staten Island'' (NYU Press: 3d ed. 2004), pp. 22\u201323 (reporting that ''Civic Fame'' is \"surprisingly, ... the largest statue in Manhattan. (No, the Statue of Liberty is not in Manhattan).\").</ref> The statue is variously reported to be supported on an [[iron]] skeleton<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/> and made over a [[steel]] frame.<ref name=\"Artwalks\"/>\n\nThe statue was designed by [[Adolph Alexander Weinman]] (1870\u20131952).<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/><ref name=\"Artwalks\"/> It was [[Art commission|commissioned]] by New York City at a cost of $9,000<ref name=\"Roberts\"/> to celebrate the [[City of Greater New York|consolidation of the five boroughs]] into the City of New York.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/> The figure\u2014described as \"graceful and unusually charming\"\u2014is barefoot and balances upon a [[globe]].<ref name=\"Artwalks\"/><ref name=\"Roberts\">Sam Roberts, ''A History of New York in 101 Objects'' (Simon & Schuster, 2014), p. 122.</ref> She carries various symbolic items: a shield bearing the [[Seal of New York City|New York City coat of arms]], a branch of leaves, and a [[mural crown]], which she holds aloft.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/><ref name=\"Artwalks\"/> The mural crown has five [[crenellation]]s or [[turret]]s, which evoke [[city wall]]s and represent the [[boroughs of New York City|five boroughs]].<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/><ref name=\"Artwalks\"/> The crown also includes [[dolphin]]s as a symbol of \"New York's maritime setting\".<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/> It is {{convert|25|ft|m}} tall<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/> and is reported to be either {{convert|580|ft|m}}<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/> or {{convert|582|ft|m}} above street level.<ref name=\"Artwalks\"/> [[Audrey Munson]] (1891\u20131996) posed for the figure.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barrypopik.com/index.php/new_york_city/entry/audrey_munson_new_yorks_civic_fame_and_miss_manhattan_san_franciscos_worlds/ |title=The Big Apple: Audrey Munson |publisher=Barrypopik.com |date=July 5, 2004 |accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref> Munson also posed for a very large number of other important allegorical [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] sculptures in New York, including those at the [[Alexander Hamilton U.S. Custom House]], [[New York Public Library Main Branch]], [[Manhattan Bridge#Arch and colonnade|Manhattan Bridge Colonnade]], and [[USS Maine National Monument|USS ''Maine'' National Monument]] at [[Columbus Circle]].<ref>Norman Taylor, ''Cinematic Perspectives on Digital Culture: Consorting with the Machine'' (Palgrave Macmillan: 2012), pp. 162\u201363.</ref><ref>Diane Rozas & Anita Bourne Gottehrer ''American Venus: The Extraordinary Life of Audrey Munson, Model and Muse'' (Balcony Press, 1999).</ref>\n\nThe statue has been variously described as the [[Statues and sculptures in New York City|largest or second-largest statue in Manhattan]], depending on whether the larger [[Statue of Liberty]] is considered as being in Manhattan.<ref name=\"Artwalks\"/><ref>Axel Nesme, \"On Stevensian Transitoriness\" in ''Wallace Stevens, New York, and Modernism'' (eds. Lisa Goldfarb & Bart Eeckhout: Routledge, 2012) (\"His gigantic gilded statue, ''Civic Fame'', still the second largest figurative statue in Manhattan\").</ref> It is similar in style to the Statue of Liberty.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/>\n\nAccording to the [[New York City Department of Citywide Administrative Services]], \"the left arm of the statue fell off and went through a skylight on the 26th floor of the Municipal Building\" (then a cafeteria) in 1936, which led to the first renovation of the statue.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/> In 1991, while the facade was undergoing renovations, ''Civic Fame'', then suffering from exposure after eight decades atop the Municipal Building, was also restored by the city government.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/><ref name=\"Roberts\"/> The statue was removed, \"regilded with 23.5-karat gold leaf, and hoisted back into position by helicopter\".<ref name=\"Roberts\"/>\n\nIn addition to ''Civic Fame'', Weinman also sculpted the allegorical [[bas-relief]] panels at the base of the building,<ref name=nycland /> as well as much of the building's other ornamentation, \"including a series of medallions, patterns, coats of arms, and several major groups of figures\" which represent various concepts: ''Civic Pride'', ''Progress'', ''Guidance'' (to the left of the entrance), ''Executive Power'' (right of the entrance), and ''Prudence''.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Agencies==\n[[File:Manhattan Municipal Building by David Shankbone edited-1 crop.jpg|thumb|A view of the building from above with [[Thurgood Marshall United States Courthouse]] in the background.]]\n\nThe following New York City public offices are located in the Manhattan Municipal Building:<ref name=\"NYDCAS\"/>\n* [[New York City Department of Citywide Administrative Services]]\n* [[New York City Department of Finance]]\n* [[New York Public Service Commission]]\n* [[Manhattan Borough President]]\n* [[New York City Public Advocate]]\n* [[New York City Comptroller]]\n* [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]\n* New York City Office of Payroll Administration\n* New York City Tax Commission\n* Field offices of the Office of the Mayor, [[New York City Department of Information Technology and Telecommunications]] (DoITT), [[New York City Department of Buildings]], New York State Office of the Inspector General, and [[New York City Department of Environmental Protection]].\n\nThe Office of the City Clerk was formerly housed in the Municipal Building; about 16,000 weddings were performed annually at the former Manhattan Marriage Bureau in the Municipal Building,<ref>{{cite news |title=Manhattan Marriage Bureau Gets Makeover |first=John |last=Del Signore |url=http://gothamist.com/2009/01/08/manhattan_marriage_bureau_gets_make.php |work=[[Gothamist]] |date=January 8, 2009 |accessdate=June 9, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409064432/http://gothamist.com/2009/01/08/manhattan_marriage_bureau_gets_make.php |archivedate=April 9, 2009 }}</ref> in civil ceremonies lasting about four minutes, before the City Clerk's Office relocated to nearby 141 Worth Street in 2009.<ref name=\"NYDCAS\"/><ref>[http://cityclerk.nyc.gov/html/home/pr_clerk_office_marriage_bureau.shtml New City Clerk's Office and Marriage Bureau Opens for Business on January 12], Office of the New York City Clerk (January 7, 2009).</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Manhattan Marriage Bureau Gets Ready to Move |first=Jen |last=Chung |url=http://gothamist.com/2008/10/05/manhattan_marriage_bureau_gets_read.php |work=[[Gothamist]] |date=October 5, 2008 |accessdate=August 7, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409064422/http://gothamist.com/2008/10/05/manhattan_marriage_bureau_gets_read.php |archivedate=April 9, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n'''Film'''\n* The Manhattan Municipal Building appears in a key scene of the 1996 film ''[[One Fine Day (film)|One Fine Day]]'', in which Jack Taylor ([[George Clooney]]) spots Manny Feldstein ([[Joe Grifasi]]) and chases him to the roof.<ref>Katz (1995), [https://books.google.com/books?id=7XA0igasljEC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Manhattan+on+Film:+Walking+Tours+of+Hollywood%27s+Fabled+Front+Lot&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAGoVChMIxujs3NWcyAIVjUGSCh3tng01#v=onepage&q=municipal%20building&f=false p.300].</ref>\n* In the film ''[[Ghostbusters]]'', the Ghostbusters team, after being released to deal with the threat, sets out from the Municipal Building with the police and National Guard as [[Bill Murray]] calls, \"Come on, let's run some red lights!\"\n* In the film ''[[\"Crocodile\" Dundee]]'' (1986), muggers inside the Municipal Building entrance to the station pull a knife on the title character ([[Paul Hogan]]) and his girlfriend Sue ([[Linda Kozlowski]]); Dundee responds by saying of the muggers' knife, \"That's not a knife.\" Pulling a larger knife of his own, he then says, \"''That{{'}}s'' a knife.\"<ref>Katz (1995), [https://books.google.com/books?id=7XA0igasljEC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Manhattan+on+Film:+Walking+Tours+of+Hollywood%27s+Fabled+Front+Lot&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAGoVChMIxujs3NWcyAIVjUGSCh3tng01#v=onepage&q=municipal%20building&f=false pp.298\u201399].</ref>\n* In the film ''[[L\u00e9on: The Professional|The Professional]]'' (1994), antagonist Stansfield, played by actor [[Gary Oldman]], works for the [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]] at the building, in office 1402.<ref>[http://www.onthesetofnewyork.com/leon.html L\u00e9on, The Professional (1994)], ''On the Set of New York'' (accessed September 27, 2015).</ref>\n\n'''Music'''\n* In the music video for the song ''[[Not Afraid]]'', rapper [[Eminem]] is depicted standing on the edge of the building's roof in multiple shots.<ref>{{Cite AV media|date=April 29, 2010|author=EminemVEVO|medium=video|title=Eminem \u2013 Not Afraid|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j5-yKhDd64s|access-date=December 13, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"225px\" heights=\"250px\">\nFile:Municipal Building Facade - New York City.jpg|<center>from below</center>\nFile:Municipal Building New York.JPG|<center>rear view, from the [[Brooklyn Bridge]]</center>\nFile:New York City Hall Park winter.jpg|<center>from [[City Hall Park]]</center>\nFile:NY City Hall Chambers Street IMG 2039.JPG|<center>from [[Chambers Street (Manhattan)|Chambers Street]]</center>\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|New York City|Architecture}}\n* [[List of New York City Borough Halls and municipal buildings]]\n* [[Early skyscrapers]]\n* [[Yule marble]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n* [http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=115520 Municipal Building, New York City]\u2014[[Emporis]]\n* Katz, Chuck, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7XA0igasljEC ''Manhattan on Film: Walking Tours of Hollywood's Fabled Front Lot''] (Limelight, 1995).\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title=[[List of largest buildings in the world|Largest office building in the world]]<br>by floor area<br>1913\u20131915 | before=[[Hudson Terminal]]  | after=[[Equitable Building (Manhattan)|Equitable Building]] | years=}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:City and town halls on the National Register of Historic Places in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Civic Center, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Government buildings completed in 1914]]\n[[Category:Government buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Government of New York City]]\n[[Category:McKim, Mead & White buildings]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Manhattan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name =Manhattan Municipal Building\n| nrhp_type =\n| image =Municipal Building - New York City.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption =\n| location= [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| locmapin = Lower Manhattan#New York City#New York#USA\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|42|46.67|N|74|0|13.99|W|display=inline,title}}\n| area =\n| built =1907\u20131914<ref name=aia4 /><ref name=nycland />\n| architect= [[William M. Kendall]]\n| architecture = [[Ancient Roman architecture|Ancient Roman]]<br />[[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]]<br />[[French Renaissance architecture|French Renaissance]]<br />[[Renaissance architecture|Renaissance]]\n| added = October 18, 1972\n| governing_body = City of New York\n| refnum=72000879<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2006a}}</ref>\n| designated_other2_name = NYC Landmark\n| designated_other2_date = February 1, 1966\n| designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n| designated_other2_link = New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission\n| designated_other2_number =\n| designated_other2_color = #ffe978\n}}\n\nThe '''David N. Dinkins Municipal Building''', originally the '''Municipal Building''' and then the '''Manhattan Municipal Building''',<ref>[http://www.nyc-architecture.com/SCC/SCC030.htm The Municipal Building], ''New York Architecture''.</ref> is a 40-story, {{Convert|580|ft|m|abbr=|adj=on}} building at 1 [[Centre Street (Manhattan)|Centre Street]] in [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], near the intersection with [[Chambers Street (Manhattan)|Chambers Street]]. The structure was built to accommodate increased governmental space demands after the [[City of Greater New York|1898 consolidation]] of the city's [[Borough (New York City)|five boroughs]], with construction beginning in 1907 and continuing through 1914.<ref name=\"aia4\">{{cite AIA4}}, p.71</ref><ref name=\"nycland\">{{cite nycland}}, p.33</ref> \n\nThe Manhattan Municipal Building's construction marked the end of the [[City Beautiful movement]] in New York. [[William M. Kendall]]<ref name=\"aia4\" /> of the noted [[architectural firm]] [[McKim, Mead & White]] designed the building, which was the first to incorporate a [[New York City Subway|subway]] station \u2013 the [[Chambers Street (BMT Nassau Street Line)|Chambers Street]] station, served by the {{NYCS trains|Nassau north}} \u2013 into its base. Enormously influential in the civic construction of other American cities, the building's [[architectural style]] has been \"variously described as [[Ancient Roman architecture|Roman Imperial]], [[Renaissance architecture|Italian Renaissance]], [[French Renaissance architecture|French Renaissance]], or [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]].\"<ref>Sarah Bradford Landau & Carl W. Condit, ''Rise of the New York Skyscraper: 1865\u20131913'' (Yale University Press, 1999), p. 374.</ref> \n\nThe Municipal Building is one of the largest governmental buildings in the world. At present, the Municipal Building is home to \"over 2,000 employees from a dozen municipal agencies in nearly 1 million square feet of office space.\"<ref name=\"NYDCAS\">[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcas/html/about/man_munibldg.shtml Manhattan Municipal Building], [[New York City Department of Citywide Administrative Services]] (accessed September 27, 2015).</ref>\n\n__TOC__\n\n==History==\n\n=== Planning and construction ===\n{{multiple image\n| align     = left\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1    = Municipal Building New York.jpg\n| width1    = 169\n| caption1  = Under construction, {{circa|1912}}\n| image2    = Colin Campbell Cooper, Chambers Street and the Municipal Building, N.Y.C.jpg\n| width2    = 180\n| caption2  = ''Chambers Street and the Municipal Building'' by [[Colin Campbell Cooper]], c. 1922\n}}\n\nIn the 1884 annual report of the City of New York, Mayor [[Franklin Edson]] declared that more space was badly needed for governmental functions. But he also noted that [[New York City Hall|City Hall]] was not expandable because its \"style of architecture was such that without marring its present symmetry, it couldn't be enlarged to the required extent.\"\n\nThe City's agencies rented space in various buildings strewn all the way from [[Downtown Manhattan]] up to [[Midtown Manhattan]], with the number of such arrangements increasing by the year. The government, desiring to cut down the amount of rent paid to private landlords, held several design competitions for a new, massive building that would be suitable to house many agencies under one roof. Mayor [[Abram Hewitt]] appointed a commission to study suitable plans and plots of land in 1888, and four competitions were held between that year and 1907.  The final competition was held by the Commissioner of Bridges, who had already secured a new plot of land to be used for a new [[tram|trolley]] hub at the Manhattan base of [[Brooklyn Bridge]]. Twelve architectural firms entered the last competition, and the winning entry was received from [[William Mitchell Kendall]],<ref name=encnyc2 /> a young partner of [[McKim, Mead & White]], which had been urged to enter the contest by Mayor [[George B. McClellan, Jr.]]<ref name=encnyc2>Willis, Carol. \"Municipal Building\" in {{cite enc-nyc2}}, pp. 863\u2013864</ref> McKim, Mead was at the time the largest architectural firm in the world, with a staff numbering over 100. Despite their standing in the architectural community, the Manhattan Municipal Building would be their first [[skyscraper]].\n\nThe building was first occupied in January 1913, and the majority of the building's offices were opened to the public by 1916.\n\n=== Later use ===\n{{Expand section|date=November 2019}}\nThe facade of the building was restored in 1990 by the architects [[Wank Adams Slavin]].<ref name=\"aia4\" />\n\nThe building was designated a [[List of New York City Landmarks|New York City landmark]] in 1966,<ref name=\"nycland\" /> and was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1972.  On October 14, 2015, the building was renamed after former mayor [[David N. Dinkins]].<ref>Ngo, Emily. [http://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/nyc-municipal-building-renamed-for-former-mayor-david-n-dinkins-1.10967492 \"NYC Municipal Building renamed for former Mayor Dinkins\"] ''[[Newsday]]'' (October 15, 2015)</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Art and architecture==\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1    = 2008-05-04 CanonS3 IMG 3076 Civic Fame crop.jpg\n | width1    = 136\n | caption1   = The gilded statue of ''Civic Fame'' at the top\n | image2    = Manhattan Municipal Building 3034848677 a09e975842b.jpg\n | width2    = 163\n | caption2  = [[Guastavino tile|Guastavino ceiling tiles]] on the south arcade\n | image3    = Municipal Building Arch.jpg\n | width3    = 150\n | caption3  = The central arch, inspired by the Roman [[Arch of Constantine]]\n}}\nThe building features various types of sculpture and relief.<ref name=\"NYDCAS\"/> The [[New York City Department of Citywide Administrative Services]] reports:\n\n{{quote|The central arch is decorated with [[Neoclassical architecture|sculpture in the Roman manner]] as was used in the [[Arch of Constantine]]. Over the side arches are rectangular allegorical panels. At the left (north), ''Civic Duty'' is represented by a woman personifying the City, accompanied by a child holding the seal of the city. On the right of the arch (south), ''Civic Pride'' shows the female personification of the city receiving tribute from her citizens. Adolph Weinman, the sculptor of ''Civic Fame'', also designed the shields that were used in the elevators, on the molding above the colonnade and again on the false colonnade above the 22nd floor. They represent [[New Amsterdam]], the [[Province of New York]] (under English rule), the City of New York, the [[County of New York]] and the State of New York.<ref name=\"NYDCAS\"/>}}\n\nThe central arch is large enough that automobile traffic once went through it. However, in modern times, [[Chambers Street (Manhattan)|Chambers Street]] has been shortened and no longer continues east through the arch. A screen of [[Corinthian column]]s flanks the arch.<ref name=nycland />\n\nThe [[terra-cotta]] [[vault (architecture)|vault]] was modeled on the entrance of the [[Palazzo Farnese]] in [[Rome]], and the south arcade has a ceiling of white [[Guastavino tile]]s.<ref name=nycland />\n\n===''Civic Fame''===\nAt the top of the Municipal Building is the statue ''Civic Fame'', installed in March 1913. The statue is a [[Gilding|gilded]] [[copper]] figure, made from about 500 pieces of hammered copper.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\">[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcas/html/about/civicfame.shtml Civic Fame] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304200909/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcas/html/about/civicfame.shtml |date=March 4, 2016 }}, [[New York City Department of Citywide Administrative Services]] (accessed September 27, 2015).</ref><ref name=\"Artwalks\">Marina Harrison & Lucy D. Rosenfeld, ''Artwalks in New York: Delightful Discoveries of Public Art and Gardens in Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens, the Bronx, and Staten Island'' (NYU Press: 3d ed. 2004), pp. 22\u201323 (reporting that ''Civic Fame'' is \"surprisingly, ... the largest statue in Manhattan. (No, the Statue of Liberty is not in Manhattan).\").</ref> The statue is variously reported to be supported on an [[iron]] skeleton<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/> and made over a [[steel]] frame.<ref name=\"Artwalks\"/>\n\nThe statue was designed by [[Adolph Alexander Weinman]] (1870\u20131952).<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/><ref name=\"Artwalks\"/> It was [[Art commission|commissioned]] by New York City at a cost of $9,000<ref name=\"Roberts\"/> to celebrate the [[City of Greater New York|consolidation of the five boroughs]] into the City of New York.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/> The figure\u2014described as \"graceful and unusually charming\"\u2014is barefoot and balances upon a [[globe]].<ref name=\"Artwalks\"/><ref name=\"Roberts\">Sam Roberts, ''A History of New York in 101 Objects'' (Simon & Schuster, 2014), p. 122.</ref> She carries various symbolic items: a shield bearing the [[Seal of New York City|New York City coat of arms]], a branch of leaves, and a [[mural crown]], which she holds aloft.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/><ref name=\"Artwalks\"/> The mural crown has five [[crenellation]]s or [[turret]]s, which evoke [[city wall]]s and represent the [[boroughs of New York City|five boroughs]].<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/><ref name=\"Artwalks\"/> The crown also includes [[dolphin]]s as a symbol of \"New York's maritime setting\".<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/> It is {{convert|25|ft|m}} tall<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/> and is reported to be either {{convert|580|ft|m}}<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/> or {{convert|582|ft|m}} above street level.<ref name=\"Artwalks\"/> [[Audrey Munson]] (1891\u20131996) posed for the figure.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barrypopik.com/index.php/new_york_city/entry/audrey_munson_new_yorks_civic_fame_and_miss_manhattan_san_franciscos_worlds/ |title=The Big Apple: Audrey Munson |publisher=Barrypopik.com |date=July 5, 2004 |accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref> Munson also posed for a very large number of other important allegorical [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] sculptures in New York, including those at the [[Alexander Hamilton U.S. Custom House]], [[New York Public Library Main Branch]], [[Manhattan Bridge#Arch and colonnade|Manhattan Bridge Colonnade]], and [[USS Maine National Monument|USS ''Maine'' National Monument]] at [[Columbus Circle]].<ref>Norman Taylor, ''Cinematic Perspectives on Digital Culture: Consorting with the Machine'' (Palgrave Macmillan: 2012), pp. 162\u201363.</ref><ref>Diane Rozas & Anita Bourne Gottehrer ''American Venus: The Extraordinary Life of Audrey Munson, Model and Muse'' (Balcony Press, 1999).</ref>\n\nThe statue has been variously described as the [[Statues and sculptures in New York City|largest or second-largest statue in Manhattan]], depending on whether the larger [[Statue of Liberty]] is considered as being in Manhattan.<ref name=\"Artwalks\"/><ref>Axel Nesme, \"On Stevensian Transitoriness\" in ''Wallace Stevens, New York, and Modernism'' (eds. Lisa Goldfarb & Bart Eeckhout: Routledge, 2012) (\"His gigantic gilded statue, ''Civic Fame'', still the second largest figurative statue in Manhattan\").</ref> It is similar in style to the Statue of Liberty.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/>\n\nAccording to the [[New York City Department of Citywide Administrative Services]], \"the left arm of the statue fell off and went through a skylight on the 26th floor of the Municipal Building\" (then a cafeteria) in 1936, which led to the first renovation of the statue.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/> In 1991, while the facade was undergoing renovations, ''Civic Fame'', then suffering from exposure after eight decades atop the Municipal Building, was also restored by the city government.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/><ref name=\"Roberts\"/> The statue was removed, \"regilded with 23.5-karat gold leaf, and hoisted back into position by helicopter\".<ref name=\"Roberts\"/>\n\nIn addition to ''Civic Fame'', Weinman also sculpted the allegorical [[bas-relief]] panels at the base of the building,<ref name=nycland /> as well as much of the building's other ornamentation, \"including a series of medallions, patterns, coats of arms, and several major groups of figures\" which represent various concepts: ''Civic Pride'', ''Progress'', ''Guidance'' (to the left of the entrance), ''Executive Power'' (right of the entrance), and ''Prudence''.<ref name=\"Civic Fame\"/>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Agencies==\n[[File:Manhattan Municipal Building by David Shankbone edited-1 crop.jpg|thumb|A view of the building from above with [[Thurgood Marshall United States Courthouse]] in the background.]]\n\nThe following New York City public offices are located in the Manhattan Municipal Building:<ref name=\"NYDCAS\"/>\n* [[New York City Department of Citywide Administrative Services]]\n* [[New York City Department of Finance]]\n* [[New York Public Service Commission]]\n* [[Manhattan Borough President]]\n* [[New York City Public Advocate]]\n* [[New York City Comptroller]]\n* [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]\n* New York City Office of Payroll Administration\n* New York City Tax Commission\n* Field offices of the Office of the Mayor, [[New York City Department of Information Technology and Telecommunications]] (DoITT), [[New York City Department of Buildings]], New York State Office of the Inspector General, and [[New York City Department of Environmental Protection]].\n\nThe Office of the City Clerk was formerly housed in the Municipal Building; about 16,000 weddings were performed annually at the former Manhattan Marriage Bureau in the Municipal Building,<ref>{{cite news |title=Manhattan Marriage Bureau Gets Makeover |first=John |last=Del Signore |url=http://gothamist.com/2009/01/08/manhattan_marriage_bureau_gets_make.php |work=[[Gothamist]] |date=January 8, 2009 |accessdate=June 9, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409064432/http://gothamist.com/2009/01/08/manhattan_marriage_bureau_gets_make.php |archivedate=April 9, 2009 }}</ref> in civil ceremonies lasting about four minutes, before the City Clerk's Office relocated to nearby 141 Worth Street in 2009.<ref name=\"NYDCAS\"/><ref>[http://cityclerk.nyc.gov/html/home/pr_clerk_office_marriage_bureau.shtml New City Clerk's Office and Marriage Bureau Opens for Business on January 12], Office of the New York City Clerk (January 7, 2009).</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Manhattan Marriage Bureau Gets Ready to Move |first=Jen |last=Chung |url=http://gothamist.com/2008/10/05/manhattan_marriage_bureau_gets_read.php |work=[[Gothamist]] |date=October 5, 2008 |accessdate=August 7, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409064422/http://gothamist.com/2008/10/05/manhattan_marriage_bureau_gets_read.php |archivedate=April 9, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n'''Film'''\n* The Manhattan Municipal Building appears in a key scene of the 1996 film ''[[One Fine Day (film)|One Fine Day]]'', in which Jack Taylor ([[George Clooney]]) spots Manny Feldstein ([[Joe Grifasi]]) and chases him to the roof.<ref>Katz (1995), [https://books.google.com/books?id=7XA0igasljEC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Manhattan+on+Film:+Walking+Tours+of+Hollywood%27s+Fabled+Front+Lot&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAGoVChMIxujs3NWcyAIVjUGSCh3tng01#v=onepage&q=municipal%20building&f=false p.300].</ref>\n* In the film ''[[Ghostbusters]]'', the Ghostbusters team, after being released to deal with the threat, sets out from the Municipal Building with the police and National Guard as [[Bill Murray]] calls, \"Come on, let's run some red lights!\"\n* In the film ''[[\"Crocodile\" Dundee]]'' (1986), muggers inside the Municipal Building entrance to the station pull a knife on the title character ([[Paul Hogan]]) and his girlfriend Sue ([[Linda Kozlowski]]); Dundee responds by saying of the muggers' knife, \"That's not a knife.\" Pulling a larger knife of his own, he then says, \"''That{{'}}s'' a knife.\"<ref>Katz (1995), [https://books.google.com/books?id=7XA0igasljEC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Manhattan+on+Film:+Walking+Tours+of+Hollywood%27s+Fabled+Front+Lot&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAGoVChMIxujs3NWcyAIVjUGSCh3tng01#v=onepage&q=municipal%20building&f=false pp.298\u201399].</ref>\n* In the film ''[[L\u00e9on: The Professional|The Professional]]'' (1994), antagonist Stansfield, played by actor [[Gary Oldman]], works for the [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]] at the building, in office 1402.<ref>[http://www.onthesetofnewyork.com/leon.html L\u00e9on, The Professional (1994)], ''On the Set of New York'' (accessed September 27, 2015).</ref>\n\n'''Music'''\n* In the music video for the song ''[[Not Afraid]]'', rapper [[Eminem]] is depicted standing on the edge of the building's roof in multiple shots.<ref>{{Cite AV media|date=April 29, 2010|author=EminemVEVO|medium=video|title=Eminem \u2013 Not Afraid|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j5-yKhDd64s|access-date=December 13, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"225px\" heights=\"250px\">\nFile:Municipal Building Facade - New York City.jpg|<center>from below</center>\nFile:Municipal Building New York.JPG|<center>rear view, from the [[Brooklyn Bridge]]</center>\nFile:New York City Hall Park winter.jpg|<center>from [[City Hall Park]]</center>\nFile:NY City Hall Chambers Street IMG 2039.JPG|<center>from [[Chambers Street (Manhattan)|Chambers Street]]</center>\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|New York City|Architecture}}\n* [[List of New York City Borough Halls and municipal buildings]]\n* [[Early skyscrapers]]\n* [[Yule marble]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n* [http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=115520 Municipal Building, New York City]\u2014[[Emporis]]\n* Katz, Chuck, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7XA0igasljEC ''Manhattan on Film: Walking Tours of Hollywood's Fabled Front Lot''] (Limelight, 1995).\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title=[[List of largest buildings in the world|Largest office building in the world]]<br>by floor area<br>1913\u20131915 | before=[[Hudson Terminal]]  | after=[[Equitable Building (Manhattan)|Equitable Building]] | years=}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Government buildings completed in 1914]]\n[[Category:Government buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Government of New York City]]\n[[Category:Civic Center, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:City and town halls on the National Register of Historic Places in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:McKim, Mead & White buildings]]\n", "name_user": "Epicgenius", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manhattan_Municipal_Building"}
{"title_page": "Illinois Fighting Illini", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox college athletics\n| name = Illinois Fighting Illini\n| logo = Illinois Fighting Illini logo.svg\n| logo_width = 125\n| university = [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]\n| association = NCAA\n| conference = [[Big Ten Conference]]\n| division = [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] ([[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]])\n| director = [[Josh Whitman]]\n| location = [[Champaign-Urbana, Illinois]]\n| teams = 21 (10 men's, 11 women's)\n| stadium = [[Memorial Stadium (Champaign)|Memorial Stadium]]\n| basketballarena = [[State Farm Center]]\n| baseballfield = [[Illinois Field]]\n| softballstadium = [[Eichelberger Field]]\n| soccerstadium = [[Illinois Soccer and Track Stadium]] \n| arena2 = {{ublist |[[Activities and Recreation Center (UIUC)|ARC Pool]] | [[Atkins Tennis Center]] | [[Huff Hall]] | [[Stone Creek Golf Course]] | [[University of Illinois Arboretum|UI Arboretum]] | [[University of Illinois Armory|UI Armory]]}}\n| nickname = Fighting Illini\n| fightsong = [[Illinois Loyalty]], [[Oskee Wow-Wow]]\n| pageurl = http://www.fightingillini.com/\n| altlogo = [[File:Illinois Fighting Illini wordmark.svg|250px]]\n}}\n[[File:Big Ten logo in Illinois colors.svg|thumb|250px|Big Ten logo in Illinois' colors]]\nThe '''Illinois Fighting Illini''' ({{IPAc-en|\u026a|l|a\u026a|n|a\u026a}}){{fix|text=stress?}} are the [[College athletics|intercollegiate athletic]] teams that represent the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]. The university offers 10 men's and 11 women's [[Varsity team|varsity]] sports.\n\nThe University operates a number of athletic facilities, including [[Memorial Stadium (Champaign)|Memorial Stadium]] for [[College football|football]], the [[State Farm Center]] for both men's and women's [[college basketball|basketball]], [[Illinois Field]] for [[College baseball|baseball]], the [[Activities and Recreation Center (UIUC)|ARC Pool]] for women's [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]] and [[Diving (sport)|diving]], the [[Atkins Tennis Center]] for men's and women's [[tennis]], [[Eichelberger Field]] for [[College softball|softball]], [[Huff Hall]] for men's and women's [[gymnastics]], women's [[volleyball]] and men's [[Collegiate wrestling|wrestling]], [[Illinois Soccer and Track Stadium]] for women's [[College soccer|soccer]] and for men's and women's outdoor [[track and field]], the [[Stone Creek Golf Course]] for men's and women's [[golf]], the [[University of Illinois Arboretum]] for [[Cross country running|cross country]] and the [[University of Illinois Armory]] for men's and women's indoor [[track and field]].\n\nThe Fighting Illini lay claim to over twenty-five National Championships dating back to 1900.\n\n==Nickname==\nThe University of Illinois official team nickname is the Fighting Illini.<ref name=\"Fighting Illini Name\">{{cite web |url=https://archives.library.illinois.edu/blog/fighting-illini-name/|title=Fighting Illini Name|work=archives.library.illinois.edu|accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref> The earliest reference of Illini appears to be mentioned in January 1874, when the campus weekly newspaper changed its name from The Student to The Illini. An editorial in the first edition of the renamed newspaper indicated that Illini was a new term. During the late 19th century and beginning of the 20th century, it was used to refer to the students, faculty, staff, and alumni of the University, as well as to the campus as a whole.<ref name=\"Fighting Illini Name FAQ\">{{cite web|url=https://archives.library.illinois.edu/features/illini.php|title=Fighting Illini FAQ|work=archives.library.illinois.edu |accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe term Illini referring to the universities athletic teams seems to come from secondhand accounts of the athletic teams. The earliest reference in the Illio yearbook appears to be one mention in the summary of the 1907 football season. The term was more widely used in the 1910s especially during the 1914, 1915, and 1916 football seasons. [[The Daily Illini]] and football programs prior to these dates do not extensively cite the term and also used the terms \"Indians,\" \"our men,\" \"Orange and Blue,\" and the \"homecomers\".<ref name=\"Fighting Illini Name FAQ\"/>\n\nThe term Fighting Illini first appeared in a January 29, 1911 newspaper article describing the basketball team's effort during a game versus Purdue. By March 3, 1911, the athletic teams appeared to have earned the Fighting Illini nickname as a formal appellation evidenced in a newspaper report. In 2005, evidence suggested Fighting Illini was first used in 1921 as part of a fundraising campaign for construction of [[Memorial Stadium (Champaign)|Memorial Stadium]], but articles discovered in 2013 show it was first used in 1911.<ref name=\"Fighting Illini Name\"/> The Fighting Illini nickname was adopted by general consensus as an unofficial school nickname sometime between 1921\u20131930. It was then used in newspaper articles, football programs and other publications eventually becoming the official nickname.<ref name=\"Fighting Illini Name\"/>\n\n== Sports sponsored ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; clear:right; margin:0 0 1em 1em;\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Illinois Fighting Illini|Men's sports|Women's sports}}\n|-\n| [[Illinois Fighting Illini baseball|Baseball]] || [[Illinois Fighting Illini women's basketball|Basketball]]\n|-\n| [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|Basketball]] || Cross country\n|-\n| Cross country || Golf\n|-\n| [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Football]] || Gymnastics\n|-\n| [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's golf|Golf]] || Soccer\n|-\n| [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's gymnastics|Gymnastics]] || [[Illinois Fighting Illini softball|Softball]]\n|-\n| [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's tennis|Tennis]] || Swimming and diving\n|-\n| Track and field<sup>\u2020</sup> || Tennis\n|-\n| Wrestling || Track and field<sup>\u2020</sup>\n|-\n| || [[Illinois Fighting Illini women's volleyball|Volleyball]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"{{NCAA secondary color cell|Illinois Fighting Illini}}\" | {{small|\u2020 \u2013 Track and field includes both indoor and outdoor}}\n|}\n\nIllinois has won 18 overall men's and women's NCAA team national championships through the 2017 NCAA athletic season.<ref name=\"NCAA NCs through 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/champs_records_book/Overall.pdf|title=NCAA Championship Summary through June 28, 2018|publisher=ncaa.org|accessdate=2018-07-03}}</ref> Illinois ranks thirty-sixth all-time in total NCAA Division I national championships through the 2017 NCAA athletic season.<ref name=\"NCAA NCs through 2017\"/>\n\n=== Baseball ===\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini baseball}}\nFighting Illini baseball has 10 NCAA Tournament appearances, 33 Big Ten championships and 4 Big Ten Tournament championships in 1989, 1990, 2000 and 2011.\n\n=== Basketball ===\n\n==== Men's basketball  ====\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball}}\nFighting Illini men's basketball titles include the 1915 [[Helms Athletic Foundation|Helms]] national championship, 5 NCAA Final Four appearances in 1949, 1951, 1952, 1989, 2005, 17 Big Ten championships and 2 Big Ten Tournament championships in 2003 and 2005. Through the end of the [[2013\u201314 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2013\u201314 season]], Illinois ranks 11th all-time in [[List of teams with the highest winning percentage in NCAA Division I men's college basketball|winning percentage]] and 14th all-time in [[List of teams with the most victories in NCAA Division I men's college basketball|wins]] among all NCAA Division I men's college basketball programs.\n\n[[File:Bristow Adams, University of Illinois football player, 1902.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A [[Bristow Adams]] poster of an Illini football player]]\n[[File:The Official National Collegiate Athletic Association football guide. The official rules book and record book of college football (1907) (14591443659).jpg|thumb|300px|right|1904 NCAA football guide featuring Illini Football. The guide was the official rules book and record book of college football]]\n\n==== Women's basketball ====\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini women's basketball}}\nFighting Illini women's basketball began play in 1974. The team won the 1997 Big Ten championship. They have made 8 NCAA Tournament appearances, including 2 Sweet Sixteen appearances in 1997 and 1998.\n\n=== Cross country ===\n==== Men's cross country ====\nThe men's cross country team carries the title of Big Ten Champions in 1921, 1947 and 1984.\n\n==== Women's cross country ====\nThe Fighting Illini women's cross country team began play in 1977. Illinois won an individual NCAA championship in 2009.\n\n=== Football ===\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini football}}\nThe University of Illinois has five national championships in football. The Fighting Illini now officially recognize the 1951 National Championship by the Boand selecting body,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/ill/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2008MediaGuide--Records.pdf |title=The Record Book |publisher=Grfx.cstv.com |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> but as recently as 2006 this was not mentioned officially by the school.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://graphics.fansonly.com/photos/schools/ill/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2006MG-TheRecordBook.pdf |title=Records |publisher=Graphics.fansonly.com |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> The team also has 15 Big Ten Championship Football victories with 8 Bowl Game Victories at the [[1947 Rose Bowl]], [[1952 Rose Bowl]], [[1964 Rose Bowl]], [[1990 Florida Citrus Bowl]], [[1994 Liberty Bowl]], [[1999 MicronPC.com Bowl]], [[2010 Texas Bowl]], and [[2011 Kraft Fight Hunger Bowl (December)|2011 Kraft Fight Hunger Bowl]].\n\n=== Golf ===\n==== Men's golf ====\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini men's golf}}\nThe men's golf team play their home matches on the [[Stone Creek Golf Course]] five miles from the university's campus, and are currently led by head coach [[Mike Small (golfer)|Mike Small]].  The Fighting Illini men's golf program has won 17 Big Ten championships and in 2013 finished as national runner-up at the [[NCAA Division I Men's Golf Championships]], which was the highest finish in the program's history. 2014 was the third time in the past four years the program had qualified for the [[match play]] portion of the NCAA Men's Golf Championships in which the final eight teams compete in a bracket format.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fightingillini.com/sports/m-golf/recaps/052614aaa.html |title=Illini Advance to NCAA Match Play for Third Time in 4 Years |publisher=University of Illinois DIA |date=May 26, 2014 |accessdate=June 25, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140709093752/http://www.fightingillini.com/sports/m-golf/recaps/052614aaa.html |archive-date=July 9, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==== Women's golf ====\nThe Fighting Illini women's golf team began play in 1975. The team has made four NCAA Tournament appearances in 2002, 2003, 2011 and 2012.\n\n=== Gymnastics ===\n==== Men's gymnastics ====\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini men's gymnastics}}\nThe men's [[gymnastics]] team have been invited to 44 NCAA tournaments and have won 10 team NCAA championships,  which is second most all-time only to [[Penn State Nittany Lions]] 12 team titles. Additionally, the Fighting Illini have won an all-time record 53 individual NCAA titles.<ref>http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/ill/sports/m-gym/auto_pdf/2012-13/misc_non_event/2013-record-book.pdf</ref> The Illini hold their competitions at [[Huff Hall|George Huff Hall]] on the [[Champaign, Illinois|Champaign]] side of campus, and the team trains and holds practices at the [[Kenney Gym]] on the [[Urbana, Illinois|Urbana]] side of campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fightingillini.com/facilities/kenneygym.html|title=Illinois Athletics|website=www.fightingillini.com|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Women's gymnastics ====\nThe Fighting Illini women's gymnastics team began play in 1974. The team won three Big Ten Championships in 1990, 1991 and 1992.\n\n=== Soccer ===\nThe Fighting Illini women's soccer team began play in 1997. The team won two Big Ten Championships in 2003 and 2011. They have made twelve NCAA Tournaments appearances in 2000, 2001, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2010, 2011, 2012 and 2013. The team has four sweet sixteen appearances in 2004, 2006, 2008, 2013 and one elite eight appearance in 2004.\n\n=== Softball ===\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini softball}}\nThe Fighting Illini softball team began play in 2000. The team has made six NCAA Tournament appearances in 2003, 2004, 2009, 2010, 2016 and 2017. The current head coach is [[Tyra Perry]].\n\n=== Swimming and diving ===\nThe Fighting Illini women's swimming and diving team began play in 1974. The team had individual NCAA champions in 1983, 1984, 1985, 1988, 1989, 1990, 1991, 1992, 1995, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006 and 2007.\n\n=== Tennis ===\n==== Men's tennis ====\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini men's tennis}}\nThe Illinois men's tennis program was founded in 1908, but has enjoyed most of its success in recent years. The Illini have been one of the most successful men's tennis programs in the nation over the past twenty seasons, winning nine consecutive Big Ten Championships from 1997\u20132005; six of seven Big Ten Tournament Championships between 1999 and 2005; appearing in the NCAA Sweet Sixteen fourteen times, including eight years in a row (2002\u201309); advancing to three NCAA Final Fours between 2003 and 2007; and winning the 2003 [[NCAA Men's Tennis Championship|NCAA National Championship]]. They have also won two ITA National Team Indoor Championships (2003, 2004)<ref>http://www.itatennis.com/Assets/ita_assets/pdf/Men$!27s+National+Team+Indoors/PastChampions.pdf</ref> and lost in the championship match three other times (1998,1999,2002). Illinois men's tennis owns the record for longest consecutive win streak in NCAA history at 64 matches, spanning from their first match of the 2002\u20132003 season and ending with a 4\u20132 defeat by [[UCLA]] in the semifinals of the 2004 NCAA Men's Tennis Tournament.\n\n==== Women's tennis ====\nThe Fighting Illini women's tennis team began play in 1975. The women's tennis team has made nine NCAA Tournament appearances in 1996, 1997, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2003, 2004, 2008 and 2010.\n\n=== Track and field ===\n==== Men's track and field ====\nThe men's Indoor Track and Field team has a total of 20 Big Ten Champion titles. For outdoor track and field the team has NCAA National Champions in 1921 1927<ref name=TF1927>The Illini were unofficial NCAA National Champions in 1927, as the NCAA did not officially score a team national championship at the competition that year.</ref> 1944, 1946, and 1947. In addition, the team carries a total of 29 Big Ten Championships.\n*Indoor Track and Field Big Ten Champions: 1912, 1913, 1914, 1916, 1920, 1921, 1924, 1928, 1946, 1947, 1951, 1952, 1953, 1954, 1958, 1977, 1981, 1987, 1988, 1989\n*Outdoor Track and Field Big Ten Champions: 1907, 1909, 1913, 1914, 1920, 1921, 1922, 1924, 1927, 1928, 1929, 1934, 1945, 1946, 1947, 1951, 1952, 1953, 1954, 1958, 1959, 1960, 1975, 1977, 1987, 1988, 1989, 1994, 2015\n\n==== Women's track and field ====\nThe Fighting Illini women's track and field team began play in 1976.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} The indoor track and field team won five Big Ten Championships in 1989, 1992, 1993, 1995 and 1996. The outdoor track and field team won the 1970 [[Association for Intercollegiate Athletics for Women]] [[AIAW Champions|national championship]] <ref>{{cite thesis|first =Virginia |last=Hunt|title =Governance of Women's Intercollegiate Athletics: an Historical Perspective|type = PhD |publisher =University of North Carolina - Greensboro|origyear=on microfilm 1977|via =University Microfilms, Ann Arbor, Michigan |year =1976|pages= 1\u2013319}}</ref><ref>Archives of the [[Association for Intercollegiate Athletics for Women]] (AIAW), Special Collections, [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] Libraries</ref> and six Big Ten Championships in 1988, 1989, 1992, 1995, 2005 and 2007.\n\n=== Volleyball ===\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini women's volleyball}}\nWomen's volleyball started in 1974.,<ref name=\"2012IlliniMediaGuide\">{{cite book |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/ill/sports/w-volley/auto_pdf/2012-13/misc_non_event/history-rec-book.pdf |title=2012 Illinois Volleyball Record Book |publisher=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign| location=Champaign, IL |year=2012 |pages=68 |accessdate=December 14, 2013}}</ref> Since moving into [[Huff Hall]] from the [[Kenney Gym and Kenney Gym Annex|Kenney Gym]] in 1990, the Illinois Volleyball team has remained in the top 10 in the nation for average home attendance. In 2013, the program broke its previous home attendance record, averaging 3,117 per match.<ref name=\"2013SeasonRecap\">{{cite news |url=http://www.fightingillini.com/sports/w-volley/recaps/121313aaf.html |title=Illinois' Most Well-Attended Season Ends at the Hand of Big Ten Foe |publisher=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign |location=Champaign, IL |year=2013 |accessdate=December 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214220002/http://www.fightingillini.com/sports/w-volley/recaps/121313aaf.html |archive-date=December 14, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Kenney Gym and Kenney Gym Annex|Kenney Gym]] served as the initial home court from 1974 through the 1989 season. Since the founding of the volleyball program in 1974, the Fighting Illini have had 30+ winning seasons.\n\n=== Wrestling ===\nThe current head coach of the University of Illinois Fighting Illini Wrestling team is Jim Heffernan, who started his tenth season in 2018. [[Huff Hall]] is the current home arena seating approximately 4,500.<ref>{{cite web |title=2013\u20132014 Wrestling Quick Facts |url=http://www.fightingillini.com/sports/m-wrestl/mtt/ill-m-wrestl-mtt.html |publisher=University of Illinois Athletics |accessdate=March 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330061451/http://www.fightingillini.com/sports/m-wrestl/mtt/ill-m-wrestl-mtt.html |archive-date=March 30, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* ''Big Ten Champions'': 1913, 1917, 1920, 1921, 1922, 1924, 1925, 1926, 1927, 1928, 1930, 1932, 1935, 1937, 1946, 1947, 1952, 2005\n* The University of Illinois has had 24 NCAA National Champions with the most recent being Jesse Delgado in 2013 and 2014 and Isaiah Martinez in 2015 and 2016.\n\n<timeline>\nDateFormat = yyyy\nImageSize  = width:900 height:auto barincrement:25\nPeriod     = from:1867 till:2015\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal\nPlotArea   = right:30 left:0 bottom:50 top:5\n\nColors = id:barcolor value:rgb(0.99,0.7,0.7)\n         id:line     value:black\n         id:bg       value:white\n\nPlotData=\n  width:15 textcolor:black shift:(5,-5) anchor:from fontsize:s\n\n  bar:1  color:skyblue from:1879 till:1881 text:Baseball (1879\u20131881, 1883\u2013present)\n  bar:1  color:white   from:1882 till:1883 text:\n  bar:1  color:skyblue from:1883 till:end  text:\n  bar:2  color:skyblue from:1890 till:end  text:Football (1890\u2013present)\n  bar:3  color:skyblue from:1890 till:end  text:Men's tennis (1890\u2013present)\n  bar:4  color:skyblue from:1901 till:end  text:Men's track & field (1901\u2013present)\n  bar:5  color:skyblue from:1905 till:end  text:Men's basketball (1905\u2013present)\n  bar:6  color:skyblue from:1905 till:end  text:Men's gymnastics (1905\u2013present)\n  bar:7  color:skyblue from:1905 till:1993 text:Men's swimming & diving (1905\u20131993)\n  bar:8  color:skyblue from:1905 till:1940 text:Men's water polo (1905\u20131940)\n  bar:9  color:skyblue from:1908 till:end  text:Men's golf (1908\u2013present)\n  bar:10  color:skyblue fr