&d=DIL19051111.2.5&srpos=4&e=------190-en-20-DIL-1--txt-txIN-illinois+water+polo+team------# |newspaper=Daily Illini |title=Water Polo and Basketball Teams Organized |date=November 11, 1905 |accessdate=November 13, 2015}}</ref> Men's fencing,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://idnc.library.illinois.edu/cgi-bin/illinois?a=d&d=DIL19110304.2.53&srpos=2&e=------191-en-20-DIL-1--txt-txIN-illinois+fencing------# |title=A Fencing Meet |newspaper=Daily Illini |date=March 4, 1911 |accessdate=November 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyillini.com/article/2015/11/athletic-scholarships-at-illinois-by-the-numbers |newspaper=Daily Illini |title=Athletic scholarships at Illinois by the numbers |date=November 5, 2015 |accessdate=November 13, 2015 |author=Figueroa, Joey |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115013713/http://www.dailyillini.com/article/2015/11/athletic-scholarships-at-illinois-by-the-numbers |archive-date=November 15, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Men's hockey,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://idnc.library.illinois.edu/cgi-bin/illinois?a=d&d=DIL19371218.2.62&srpos=1&e=------193-en-20-DIL-1--txt-txIN-illinois+hockey------# |title=Hockey-Coach |newspaper=Daily Illini |date=December 18, 1937 |accessdate=November 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://idnc.library.illinois.edu/cgi-bin/illinois?a=d&d=DIL19450720.2.57&srpos=11&e=------194-en-20-DIL-1--txt-txIN-illinois+hockey------# |title=After the Deadline |author=Roberts, Glenn |date=July 20, 1945 |accessdate=November 13, 2015 |newspaper=Daily Illini}}</ref> Men's polo,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://idnc.library.illinois.edu/cgi-bin/illinois?a=d&d=DIL19411008.2.76&srpos=2&e=------194-en-20--1--txt-txIN-illini+horse+polo------# |newspaper=Daily Illini |title=Illini Polo Rises After 9 Year Struggle |date=October 8, 1941 |accessdate=November 13, 2015 |author=Adams, Jack}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://idnc.library.illinois.edu/cgi-bin/illinois?a=d&d=DIL19340410.2.76&srpos=19&e=------193-en-20--1--txt-txIN-illini+outdoor+polo------# |newspaper=Daily Illini |title=Sport Formerly Closed to Men not in ROTC |date=April 10, 1934 |accessdate=November 13, 2015 |author=Talbot, Phil}}</ref> Men's soccer,<ref name=\"UI History DI\">{{cite web |url=http://idnc.library.illinois.edu/cgi-bin/illinois?a=d&d=DIL19700801.2.200&srpos=13&e=------197-en-20-DIL-1--txt-txIN-illinois+soccer+varsity------# |title=UI sports started small , now big business here Just check the ticket price |date=July 1, 1970 |author=Stoffel, Ron |accessdate=November 13, 2015 |newspaper=Daily Illini}}</ref> Men's water polo<ref name=\"UI BB and WP\" /><ref name=\"UI History DI\" />\n\n==Former varsity sports==\nIllinois fencing won National Championships in 1956 and 1958. Fencing was dropped as a varsity sport in 1993. Men's swimming and diving was dropped as a varsity sport in 1993, but were Big Ten Champions in 1911, 1912 and 1913.\n\n== Club sports ==\nClub sports include [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's ice hockey|men's ice hockey]], women's ice hockey, men's lacrosse, [[Illini Rowing|rowing]], men's and women's rugby, tennis, [[Illinois Men's Volleyball Club|men's volleyball]], men's and women's soccer, men's and women's ultimate frisbee, men's and women's cross country, men's and women's track and field, and men's and women's boxing.\n\n=== Boxing ===\nBoth the men's and women's boxing teams compete as part of the [[United States Intercollegiate Boxing Association]]. Illinois hosted the USIBA national championships in 2018, and the men's team won the 2018 and 2019 tournaments.<ref name=\"USIBA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.collegeboxing.org/national-tournament#champions |title=Champions -- USIBA |accessdate=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7TfAWdXMC5M |title=USIBA 2019 National Tournament Finals 3/24/19}}</ref>\n\n=== Ice hockey ===\n{{main| Illinois Fighting Illini men's ice hockey}}\nThe men's ice hockey team has played in the Division I [[Central States Collegiate Hockey League]] conference since 1979, which is part of the [[American Collegiate Hockey Association]] (ACHA), winning national championships in 2005 and 2008, with runner-up finishes in 2009 and 2018. A second team competes in the Division II [[Mid-American Collegiate Hockey Association]]. A feasibility study published in March 2018, and commissioned by the [[National Hockey League|NHL]], [[National Hockey League Players' Association|NHLPA]], and College Hockey, Inc., found a high probability of success for the hockey program to transition to [[NCAA Division I]]. <ref>{{cite web|title=Why Illini Hockey|url=http://www.whyillinihockey.com|publisher=University of Illinois Athletics |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Feasibility study: UI setting just right for hockey |url=http://www.news-gazette.com/sports/illini-sports/recruiting/2018-03-08/feasibility-study-ui-setting-just-right-hockey.html |publisher=[[The News-Gazette (Champaign-Urbana)]] |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Men's rugby ===\nFounded in 1963, the University of Illinois Men's Rugby Football Club plays in [[College Premier Division|Division 1-A]] in the [[Big Ten Universities]] conference. The Illini have experienced success in [[college rugby]], including winning several Big 10 championships in the 1980s and reaching the national semifinals in 1980, 1983 and 1985.<ref>U of I Rugby, Illinois Men's Rugby Football Club, http://uofirugby.com/en/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120919045647/http://uofirugby.com/en |date=September 19, 2012 }}</ref><ref>Rugby Mag, DII Bottom Dweller to DI-A, Illinois Opens BTU Conference Play Saturday, September 27, 2012, http://www.rugbymag.com/college-premier-league-/5909-dii-bottom-dweller-to-di-a-illinois-opens-btu-conference-play-saturday.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624133937/http://www.rugbymag.com/college-premier-league-/5909-dii-bottom-dweller-to-di-a-illinois-opens-btu-conference-play-saturday.html |date=June 24, 2013 }}</ref> The Illini play their home matches in Urbana at the Complex Fields.\n\n=== Wheelchair basketball ===\n{{main|University of Illinois Wheelchair Basketball}}\nThe men's wheelchair basketball team was founded in 1948 by Dr. Timothy Nugent in response to a large number of disabled veterans using the [[G.I. Bill]] to attend the University of Illinois.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=yHtuwDexqcYC&lpg=PA13&dq=tim%20nugent%20wheelchair%20baseball&pg=PA13#v=onepage&q=tim%20nugent%20wheelchair%20baseball&f=false |title=Wheelchair Champions: A History of Wheelchair Sports |last=Savitz |first=Harriet |date=2006 |location=Lincoln |publisher=iUniverse |isbn=978-0595385225}}</ref> Dr. Nugent later started a women's team in 1970. A total of 29 national championships are claimed between the men and women's teams.\n\n=== Rowing ===\n{{main|Illini Rowing}}\nFounded in 2005, Illini Rowing is one of the youngest [[college rowing|university rowing teams]] in the country. They practice on [[Clinton Lake (Illinois)| Clinton Lake]] and in the [[Activities and Recreation Center (UIUC)| ARC]].<ref>http://www.illinirowing.com/facilities/</ref> On Clinton Lake, they host the Illinois Collegiate Rowing Invitational where they race against many other midwestern universities.<ref>http://www.illinirowing.com/events/icri/</ref> They compete across the country in the [[American Collegiate Rowing Association]].<ref>https://americancollegiaterowing.com/members/greatlakes.html</ref>\n\n== Athletic facilities ==\n[[File:MemorialStadiumIllinois.jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Memorial Stadium (Champaign)|Memorial Stadium]] with State Farm Center in background]]\n[[Image:Assembly-hall-01.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[State Farm Center]]]]\n\n=== Current facilities ===\n*[[Activities and Recreation Center (UIUC)|Activities and Recreation Center]] (ARC Pool) \u2014 Women's swimming and diving\n*[[Atkins Tennis Center]] \u2014 Men's and women's tennis\n*[[Eichelberger Field]] \u2014 Softball\n*[[Huff Hall]] \u2014 Men's and women's gymnastics, women's volleyball, wrestling\n*[[Illinois Field]] \u2014 Baseball\n*[[Illinois Soccer and Track Stadium]] \u2014 Women's soccer, Men's and women's outdoor track and field\n*[[Memorial Stadium (Champaign)|Memorial Stadium]] \u2014 Football\n*[[State Farm Center]] (formerly Assembly Hall) \u2014 Men's and women's basketball\n*[[Stone Creek Golf Course]] \u2014 Men's and women's golf\n*[[University of Illinois Arboretum]] \u2014 Men's and women's cross country\n*[[University of Illinois Armory]] \u2014 Men's and women's indoor track and field\n\n=== Practice facilities ===\n*Demirjian Golf Practice Facility \u2014 Men's and women's golf indoor practice facility \n*Irwin Indoor Practice Facility \u2014 Football, women's soccer, baseball, softball\n*[[Kenney Gym and Kenney Gym Annex]] \u2014 Men's and women's gymnastics\n*Lauritsen/Wohlers Outdoor Golf Practice Facility \u2014 Men's and women's golf outdoor practice facility\n*U of I Orange and Blue Golf Courses \u2014 Men's and women's golf short-game practice center\n\n=== Former facilities ===\n*[[Huff Hall]] \u2014 Men's basketball (1925\u20131963)\n*[[Illinois Field (1884)|Original Illinois Field]] \u2014 Baseball (1884\u20131987) and football (1893\u20131922)\n*[[Kenney Gym and Kenney Gym Annex]] \u2014 Men's basketball (1905\u20131925)\n\n===Club and intramural facilities===\n*[[Activities and Recreation Center (UIUC)|Activities and Recreation Center]] \u2014 Intramural sports\n*[[Complex Fields (UIUC)|Complex Fields]] \u2014 Intramural sports\n*[[UIUC Campus Recreation Center \u2013 East (CRCE)|CRCE]] \u2014 Intramural sports \n*[[University of Illinois Ice Arena]] \u2014 Men's and women's club hockey, Synchronized skating\n\n==Illinois traditions==\n\n=== Marching Illini ===\n[[Image:MarchingIlliniUSA.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The [[Marching Illini]] in USA Formation during ''Patriotic Medley'' from the traditional pregame show]]\n{{Main|Marching Illini}}\nThe Marching Illini is the [[marching band]] of the university. The Marching Illini is an organization which annually includes approximately 350 students. Part of the College of Fine and Applied Arts and the School of Music, the Marching Illini represent virtually every college, discipline, and major on the University's diverse Urbana-Champaign campus. The band primarily performs before, during, and after University of Illinois home football games. The band also performs an indoor concert at the Krannert Center for the Performing Arts featuring special lighting effects, performances by individual sections, and slightly pithy comic routines. The [[Sousa Archives and Center for American Music]] houses a collection of University Band recordings and performances and recording sessions from 1940\u20131987.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.library.illinois.edu/archives/archon/index.php?p=collections/findingaid&id=2114&q=university+band|title=University Bands Tape Recordings, 1942\u20131987 \u2013 The Sousa Archives and Center for American Music |work=illinois.edu}}</ref> The band has several traditions such as the Pregame Show, Three-In-One, [[Illinois Loyalty]] and [[Oskee Wow-Wow]].\n\n=== Illinois Loyalty ===\n{{Main article|Illinois Loyalty}}\nIllinois Loyalty is the main school song of the university. It was first performed on March 3, 1906 and is one of the oldest songs of its kind in the United States. The song was written by Thacher Howland Guild (1879-1914), instructor in rhetoric and a member of the band's solo cornet section.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/jukebox/recordings/detail/id/4468/|title=Illinois Loyalty March, recorded 1916-12-05 by the Victor Military Band|author=Thatcher Howland Guild|work=Library of Congress National Jukebox|publisher=Victor Records|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref> Due to the song's length, it is normally played only at the beginning, halftime, and end of football games.\n\n=== Oskee Wow-Wow ===\n{{Main article|Oskee Wow-Wow}}\nOskee Wow-Wow is the official fight song of the University of Illinois.<ref name=\"Oskee Wow-Wow\">{{cite web|url=http://uihistories.library.illinois.edu/cgi-bin/cview?SITEID=1&ID=335|title=University Yells|work=uihistories.library.illinois.edu|accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref> Most commonly, it is played \"from the hold\" at the start of the chorus, when the \"O\" in \"Oskee Wow-Wow\" is held out. This version is played after first downs and touchdowns in [[American football|football]], and leading into time outs in [[basketball]].  Coincidentally, the buzzers at nearly every arena are in the same chord as the hold.\n\nFor many years, the band started playing the song \"from the top\" toward the end of the warmup period in basketball. When conducted correctly, the \"hold\" is played just as the buzzer sounds.\n\n=== Oskee Wow-Wow yell ===\nThe Oskee Wow-Wow yell is a University of Illinois spirit yell originated in 1899. The yell was modified in 1912 and 1916.<ref name=\"Oskee Wow-Wow\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/opinion/letters-editor/2015-08-11/oskee-wow-wow-predates-chief.html|title='Oskee Wow Wow' predates the Chief |work=news-gazette.com|accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Athletic directors ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Edward K. Hall]] (1892\u20131894)\n* Fred D. Dodge (1894\u20131895)\n* Henry H. Everett (1895\u20131898)\n* Jacob K. Shell (1898\u20131901)\n* [[George Huff (coach)|George Huff]] (1901\u20131936)\n* Wendell S. Wilson (1936\u20131941)\n* [[Douglas R. Mills]] (1941\u20131966)\n* Leslie Bryan {{small|(interim)}} (1966\u20131967)\n* [[Gene Vance]] (1967\u20131972)\n* Charles E. Flynn {{small|(interim)}} (1972)\n* Cecil Coleman (1972\u20131979)\n* [[Ray Eliot]] {{small|(interim)}} (1979)\n* [[Neale Stoner]] (1980\u20131988)\n* [[Ron Guenther]] {{small|(interim)}} (1988)\n* Karol A. Kahrs {{small|(interim)}} (1988)\n* [[John Mackovic]] (1988\u20131991)\n* Robert Todd {{small|(interim)}} (1991\u20131992)\n* [[Ron Guenther]] (1992\u20132011)\n* [[Mike Thomas (athletic director)|Mike Thomas]] (2011\u20132015)\n* Paul Kowalczyk {{small|(interim)}} (2015)\n* [[Josh Whitman]] (2016\u2013present)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{Main|List of University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign people#sports}}\nThe University has a number of notable alumni and administrators in the world of athletics. In football, notable Alumni include [[Dick Butkus]], [[Red Grange]], [[Jeff George]], [[Simeon Rice]], [[Ray Nitschke]] and [[George Halas]]. Famous basketball alumni include [[Dee Brown (basketball, born 1984)|Dee Brown]], [[Deron Williams]], [[Luther Head]], [[Derek Harper]], [[Nick Anderson]], [[Chuck Carney]], [[Brian Cook]], [[Kendall Gill]], [[Steve Bardo]], [[Jerry Colangelo]], and [[Johnny Orr (basketball, born 1927)|Johnny Orr]]. Notable athletes in baseball include [[Lou Boudreau]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=boudrlo01|title=Lou Boudreau Stats|publisher=Baseball Almanac|accessdate= October 30, 2012}}</ref> [[Hoot Evers]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=evers01|title=Hoot Evers Stats|publisher=Baseball Almanac|accessdate= October 30, 2012}}</ref> and [[Ken Holtzman]]. The University has also a number of Olympic athletes that include [[George Kerr (athlete)|George Kerr]], [[Don Laz]], [[Daniel Kinsey]], [[Harold Osborn]], [[Bob Richards]], and [[Justin Spring]],\n\n==Symbol controversy==\n{{further|Chief Illiniwek}}\nFrom 1926 to 2007, [[Chief Illiniwek]] was the symbol for the Fighting Illini. Chief Illiniwek was a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] symbol portrayed by a white student.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.si.com/more-sports/2007/10/30/chiefilliniwek | title=Chief concern | publisher=Sports Illustrated | date=October 30, 2007 | author=Zirin, Dave | accessdate=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Chief Illiniwek symbolized the [[Illinois Confederation|Illini]], a confederation of indigenous tribes who historically had inhabited much of present-day Illinois; however the clothing and regalia for the symbol was from the [[Sioux]] nation. Chief Illiniwek would perform during halftime at Illinois football and basketball games, wearing a feathered headdress and buckskin clothes, and dancing while the [[Marching Illini|marching band]] played \"Three in One\", an arrangement of three original songs.\n\nIn 2005, the Chief was one of 18 mascots (though Illiniwek was considered a symbol and not a mascot) cited as \"hostile or abusive\" by the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] in a [[NCAA Native American mascot decision|policy]] that banned schools from full participation in postseason activities as long as they continued to use such mascots.<ref>{{cite web |date=August 12, 2005 |url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/news/story?id=2125735 |title=NCAA American Indian Mascot Ban Will Begin Feb. 1 |website=ESPN |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref>  The University of Illinois retired Chief Illiniwek in 2007.  Debate about the Chief has continued to this day.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Quinatana |date=September 13, 2018 |url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/Exhaustion-Confusion-and/244513 |title='Exhaustion, Confusion, and Anger': U. of Illinois Finds a Community at Odds over Old Mascot |website=The Chronicle of Higher Education |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Shannon |last=Ryan |date=March 7, 2016 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-chief-illiniwek-illinois-spt-0307-20160306-story.html |title=Illinois Students Try to Keep Chief Alive Despite Decades of Criticism |website=Chicago Tribune |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref>  The university chancellor appointed a Commission on Native Imagery to recommend ways \"to provide closure, healing and reconciliation... to facilitate the establishment of new traditions... [and] to honor and partner with the Native Nations for whom Illinois is their ancestral home.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Julie |last=Wurth |date=November 30, 2018 |url=http://www.news-gazette.com/news/local/2018-11-30/ui-chancellor-chief-panel-tasked-only-with-finding-path-forward-not-paving-it |title=UI Chancellor: Chief Panel Tasked Only with Finding Path Forward, Not Paving It |website=The News-Gazette |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Fighting Illini are one of three [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] programs that do not have a mascot.  (The other two are the [[Michigan Wolverines|Wolverines]] and the [[Indiana Hoosiers|Hoosiers]].)<ref>{{cite web |first1=Tim |last1=Bannon |first2=Phil |last2=Rosenthal |date=March 13, 2019 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-spt-viz-big-ten-mascots-ranked-20190313-story.html |title=Ohio State Has the Best Big Ten Mascot and Iowa Has the Worst: We Rank \u2013 and Try to Explain \u2014 Them All |website=Chicago Tribune |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2020 student elections, the student body voted 4222 to 3597 for a preliminary proposal to adopt a new mascot, the [[belted kingfisher]]. The female belted kingfisher, who is \"naturally true to the orange and blue\", would be the first female mascot in the Big Ten.<ref>{{cite web | date=March 9, 2020 |url=https://uofi.app.box.com/s/5kpcz4b5o75nc2ykn7zk4w6axfv3qull/file/631059370269 | title=Campus Student Elections Commission 2020 Student Elections}}</ref> The referendum was downplayed by the university administration who said that the \"results will be shared with the university administration and the board of trustees but will not result in a new mascot at this time.\" <ref>{{cite web | date=March 10, 2020| url = https://www.news-gazette.com/news/after-the-vote-no-plans-to-choose-mascot-now-ui/article_f73b9496-6146-5b5b-8e7f-3e6fb6b1c432.html?fbclid=IwAR0_cBeprheCw6DcqFMZBzhKL8AOYJjLqQzZ_9ApfPMpPmvsyJKvnwvbXTw#utm_campaign=blox&utm_source=facebook&utm_medium=social| title=After the vote: No plans to choose mascot now, UI chancellor says | first1=Tim | last1=Ditman | website=News Gazette | access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign athletics}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign campus}}\n{{Big Ten Conference navbox}}\n{{Illinois Sports}}\n\n[[Category:Illinois Fighting Illini| ]]\n[[Category:1879 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1879]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox college athletics\n| name = Illinois Fighting Illini\n| logo = Illinois Fighting Illini logo.svg\n| logo_width = 125\n| university = [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]\n| association = NCAA\n| conference = [[Big Ten Conference]]\n| division = [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] ([[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]])\n| director = [[Josh Whitman]]\n| location = [[Champaign-Urbana, Illinois]]\n| teams = 21 (10 men's, 11 women's)\n| stadium = [[Memorial Stadium (Champaign)|Memorial Stadium]]\n| basketballarena = [[State Farm Center]]\n| baseballfield = [[Illinois Field]]\n| softballstadium = [[Eichelberger Field]]\n| soccerstadium = [[Illinois Soccer and Track Stadium]] \n| arena2 = {{ublist |[[Activities and Recreation Center (UIUC)|ARC Pool]] | [[Atkins Tennis Center]] | [[Huff Hall]] | [[Stone Creek Golf Course]] | [[University of Illinois Arboretum|UI Arboretum]] | [[University of Illinois Armory|UI Armory]]}}\n| nickname = Fighting Illini\n| fightsong = [[Illinois Loyalty]], [[Oskee Wow-Wow]]\n| pageurl = http://www.fightingillini.com/\n| altlogo = [[File:Illinois Fighting Illini wordmark.svg|250px]]\n}}\n[[File:Big Ten logo in Illinois colors.svg|thumb|250px|Big Ten logo in Illinois' colors]]\nThe '''Illinois Fighting Illini''' ({{IPAc-en|\u026a|l|a\u026a|n|a\u026a}}){{fix|text=stress?}} are the [[College athletics|intercollegiate athletic]] teams that represent the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]. The university offers 10 men's and 11 women's [[Varsity team|varsity]] sports.\n\nThe University operates a number of athletic facilities, including [[Memorial Stadium (Champaign)|Memorial Stadium]] for [[College football|football]], the [[State Farm Center]] for both men's and women's [[college basketball|basketball]], [[Illinois Field]] for [[College baseball|baseball]], the [[Activities and Recreation Center (UIUC)|ARC Pool]] for women's [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]] and [[Diving (sport)|diving]], the [[Atkins Tennis Center]] for men's and women's [[tennis]], [[Eichelberger Field]] for [[College softball|softball]], [[Huff Hall]] for men's and women's [[gymnastics]], women's [[volleyball]] and men's [[Collegiate wrestling|wrestling]], [[Illinois Soccer and Track Stadium]] for women's [[College soccer|soccer]] and for men's and women's outdoor [[track and field]], the [[Stone Creek Golf Course]] for men's and women's [[golf]], the [[University of Illinois Arboretum]] for [[Cross country running|cross country]] and the [[University of Illinois Armory]] for men's and women's indoor [[track and field]].\n\nThe Fighting Illini lay claim to over twenty-five National Championships dating back to 1900.\n\n==Nickname==\nThe University of Illinois official team nickname is the Fighting Illini.<ref name=\"Fighting Illini Name\">{{cite web |url=https://archives.library.illinois.edu/blog/fighting-illini-name/|title=Fighting Illini Name|work=archives.library.illinois.edu|accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref> The earliest reference of Illini appears to be mentioned in January 1874, when the campus weekly newspaper changed its name from The Student to The Illini. An editorial in the first edition of the renamed newspaper indicated that Illini was a new term. During the late 19th century and beginning of the 20th century, it was used to refer to the students, faculty, staff, and alumni of the University, as well as to the campus as a whole.<ref name=\"Fighting Illini Name FAQ\">{{cite web|url=https://archives.library.illinois.edu/features/illini.php|title=Fighting Illini FAQ|work=archives.library.illinois.edu |accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe term Illini referring to the universities athletic teams seems to come from secondhand accounts of the athletic teams. The earliest reference in the Illio yearbook appears to be one mention in the summary of the 1907 football season. The term was more widely used in the 1910s especially during the 1914, 1915, and 1916 football seasons. [[The Daily Illini]] and football programs prior to these dates do not extensively cite the term and also used the terms \"Indians,\" \"our men,\" \"Orange and Blue,\" and the \"homecomers\".<ref name=\"Fighting Illini Name FAQ\"/>\n\nThe term Fighting Illini first appeared in a January 29, 1911 newspaper article describing the basketball team's effort during a game versus Purdue. By March 3, 1911, the athletic teams appeared to have earned the Fighting Illini nickname as a formal appellation evidenced in a newspaper report. In 2005, evidence suggested Fighting Illini was first used in 1921 as part of a fundraising campaign for construction of [[Memorial Stadium (Champaign)|Memorial Stadium]], but articles discovered in 2013 show it was first used in 1911.<ref name=\"Fighting Illini Name\"/> The Fighting Illini nickname was adopted by general consensus as an unofficial school nickname sometime between 1921\u20131930. It was then used in newspaper articles, football programs and other publications eventually becoming the official nickname.<ref name=\"Fighting Illini Name\"/>\n\n== Sports sponsored ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; clear:right; margin:0 0 1em 1em;\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Illinois Fighting Illini|Men's sports|Women's sports}}\n|-\n| [[Illinois Fighting Illini baseball|Baseball]] || [[Illinois Fighting Illini women's basketball|Basketball]]\n|-\n| [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|Basketball]] || Cross country\n|-\n| Cross country || Golf\n|-\n| [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Football]] || Gymnastics\n|-\n| [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's golf|Golf]] || Soccer\n|-\n| [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's gymnastics|Gymnastics]] || [[Illinois Fighting Illini softball|Softball]]\n|-\n| [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's tennis|Tennis]] || Swimming and diving\n|-\n| Track and field<sup>\u2020</sup> || Tennis\n|-\n| Wrestling || Track and field<sup>\u2020</sup>\n|-\n| || [[Illinois Fighting Illini women's volleyball|Volleyball]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"{{NCAA secondary color cell|Illinois Fighting Illini}}\" | {{small|\u2020 \u2013 Track and field includes both indoor and outdoor}}\n|}\n\nIllinois has won 18 overall men's and women's NCAA team national championships through the 2017 NCAA athletic season.<ref name=\"NCAA NCs through 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/champs_records_book/Overall.pdf|title=NCAA Championship Summary through June 28, 2018|publisher=ncaa.org|accessdate=2018-07-03}}</ref> Illinois ranks thirty-sixth all-time in total NCAA Division I national championships through the 2017 NCAA athletic season.<ref name=\"NCAA NCs through 2017\"/>\n\n=== Baseball ===\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini baseball}}\nFighting Illini baseball has 10 NCAA Tournament appearances, 33 Big Ten championships and 4 Big Ten Tournament championships in 1989, 1990, 2000 and 2011.\n\n=== Basketball ===\n\n==== Men's basketball  ====\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball}}\nFighting Illini men's basketball titles include the 1915 [[Helms Athletic Foundation|Helms]] national championship, 5 NCAA Final Four appearances in 1949, 1951, 1952, 1989, 2005, 17 Big Ten championships and 2 Big Ten Tournament championships in 2003 and 2005. Through the end of the [[2013\u201314 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2013\u201314 season]], Illinois ranks 11th all-time in [[List of teams with the highest winning percentage in NCAA Division I men's college basketball|winning percentage]] and 14th all-time in [[List of teams with the most victories in NCAA Division I men's college basketball|wins]] among all NCAA Division I men's college basketball programs.\n\n[[File:Bristow Adams, University of Illinois football player, 1902.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A [[Bristow Adams]] poster of an Illini football player]]\n[[File:The Official National Collegiate Athletic Association football guide. The official rules book and record book of college football (1907) (14591443659).jpg|thumb|300px|right|1904 NCAA football guide featuring Illini Football. The guide was the official rules book and record book of college football]]\n\n==== Women's basketball ====\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini women's basketball}}\nFighting Illini women's basketball began play in 1974. The team won the 1997 Big Ten championship. They have made 8 NCAA Tournament appearances, including 2 Sweet Sixteen appearances in 1997 and 1998.\n\n=== Cross country ===\n==== Men's cross country ====\nThe men's cross country team carries the title of Big Ten Champions in 1921, 1947 and 1984.\n\n==== Women's cross country ====\nThe Fighting Illini women's cross country team began play in 1977. Illinois won an individual NCAA championship in 2009.\n\n=== Football ===\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini football}}\nThe University of Illinois has five national championships in football. The Fighting Illini now officially recognize the 1951 National Championship by the Boand selecting body,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/ill/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2008MediaGuide--Records.pdf |title=The Record Book |publisher=Grfx.cstv.com |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> but as recently as 2006 this was not mentioned officially by the school.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://graphics.fansonly.com/photos/schools/ill/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2006MG-TheRecordBook.pdf |title=Records |publisher=Graphics.fansonly.com |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> The team also has 15 Big Ten Championship Football victories with 8 Bowl Game Victories at the [[1947 Rose Bowl]], [[1952 Rose Bowl]], [[1964 Rose Bowl]], [[1990 Florida Citrus Bowl]], [[1994 Liberty Bowl]], [[1999 MicronPC.com Bowl]], [[2010 Texas Bowl]], and [[2011 Kraft Fight Hunger Bowl (December)|2011 Kraft Fight Hunger Bowl]].\n\n=== Golf ===\n==== Men's golf ====\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini men's golf}}\nThe men's golf team play their home matches on the [[Stone Creek Golf Course]] five miles from the university's campus, and are currently led by head coach [[Mike Small (golfer)|Mike Small]].  The Fighting Illini men's golf program has won 17 Big Ten championships and in 2013 finished as national runner-up at the [[NCAA Division I Men's Golf Championships]], which was the highest finish in the program's history. 2014 was the third time in the past four years the program had qualified for the [[match play]] portion of the NCAA Men's Golf Championships in which the final eight teams compete in a bracket format.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fightingillini.com/sports/m-golf/recaps/052614aaa.html |title=Illini Advance to NCAA Match Play for Third Time in 4 Years |publisher=University of Illinois DIA |date=May 26, 2014 |accessdate=June 25, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140709093752/http://www.fightingillini.com/sports/m-golf/recaps/052614aaa.html |archive-date=July 9, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==== Women's golf ====\nThe Fighting Illini women's golf team began play in 1975. The team has made four NCAA Tournament appearances in 2002, 2003, 2011 and 2012.\n\n=== Gymnastics ===\n==== Men's gymnastics ====\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini men's gymnastics}}\nThe men's [[gymnastics]] team have been invited to 44 NCAA tournaments and have won 10 team NCAA championships,  which is second most all-time only to [[Penn State Nittany Lions]] 12 team titles. Additionally, the Fighting Illini have won an all-time record 53 individual NCAA titles.<ref>http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/ill/sports/m-gym/auto_pdf/2012-13/misc_non_event/2013-record-book.pdf</ref> The Illini hold their competitions at [[Huff Hall|George Huff Hall]] on the [[Champaign, Illinois|Champaign]] side of campus, and the team trains and holds practices at the [[Kenney Gym]] on the [[Urbana, Illinois|Urbana]] side of campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fightingillini.com/facilities/kenneygym.html|title=Illinois Athletics|website=www.fightingillini.com|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Women's gymnastics ====\nThe Fighting Illini women's gymnastics team began play in 1974. The team won three Big Ten Championships in 1990, 1991 and 1992.\n\n=== Soccer ===\nThe Fighting Illini women's soccer team began play in 1997. The team won two Big Ten Championships in 2003 and 2011. They have made twelve NCAA Tournaments appearances in 2000, 2001, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2010, 2011, 2012 and 2013. The team has four sweet sixteen appearances in 2004, 2006, 2008, 2013 and one elite eight appearance in 2004.\n\n=== Softball ===\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini softball}}\nThe Fighting Illini softball team began play in 2000. The team has made six NCAA Tournament appearances in 2003, 2004, 2009, 2010, 2016 and 2017. The current head coach is [[Tyra Perry]].\n\n=== Swimming and diving ===\nThe Fighting Illini women's swimming and diving team began play in 1974. The team had individual NCAA champions in 1983, 1984, 1985, 1988, 1989, 1990, 1991, 1992, 1995, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006 and 2007.\n\n=== Tennis ===\n==== Men's tennis ====\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini men's tennis}}\nThe Illinois men's tennis program was founded in 1908, but has enjoyed most of its success in recent years. The Illini have been one of the most successful men's tennis programs in the nation over the past twenty seasons, winning nine consecutive Big Ten Championships from 1997\u20132005; six of seven Big Ten Tournament Championships between 1999 and 2005; appearing in the NCAA Sweet Sixteen fourteen times, including eight years in a row (2002\u201309); advancing to three NCAA Final Fours between 2003 and 2007; and winning the 2003 [[NCAA Men's Tennis Championship|NCAA National Championship]]. They have also won two ITA National Team Indoor Championships (2003, 2004)<ref>http://www.itatennis.com/Assets/ita_assets/pdf/Men$!27s+National+Team+Indoors/PastChampions.pdf</ref> and lost in the championship match three other times (1998,1999,2002). Illinois men's tennis owns the record for longest consecutive win streak in NCAA history at 64 matches, spanning from their first match of the 2002\u20132003 season and ending with a 4\u20132 defeat by [[UCLA]] in the semifinals of the 2004 NCAA Men's Tennis Tournament.\n\n==== Women's tennis ====\nThe Fighting Illini women's tennis team began play in 1975. The women's tennis team has made nine NCAA Tournament appearances in 1996, 1997, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2003, 2004, 2008 and 2010.\n\n=== Track and field ===\n==== Men's track and field ====\nThe men's Indoor Track and Field team has a total of 20 Big Ten Champion titles. For outdoor track and field the team has NCAA National Champions in 1921 1927<ref name=TF1927>The Illini were unofficial NCAA National Champions in 1927, as the NCAA did not officially score a team national championship at the competition that year.</ref> 1944, 1946, and 1947. In addition, the team carries a total of 29 Big Ten Championships.\n*Indoor Track and Field Big Ten Champions: 1912, 1913, 1914, 1916, 1920, 1921, 1924, 1928, 1946, 1947, 1951, 1952, 1953, 1954, 1958, 1977, 1981, 1987, 1988, 1989\n*Outdoor Track and Field Big Ten Champions: 1907, 1909, 1913, 1914, 1920, 1921, 1922, 1924, 1927, 1928, 1929, 1934, 1945, 1946, 1947, 1951, 1952, 1953, 1954, 1958, 1959, 1960, 1975, 1977, 1987, 1988, 1989, 1994, 2015\n\n==== Women's track and field ====\nThe Fighting Illini women's track and field team began play in 1976.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} The indoor track and field team won five Big Ten Championships in 1989, 1992, 1993, 1995 and 1996. The outdoor track and field team won the 1970 [[Association for Intercollegiate Athletics for Women]] [[AIAW Champions|national championship]] <ref>{{cite thesis|first =Virginia |last=Hunt|title =Governance of Women's Intercollegiate Athletics: an Historical Perspective|type = PhD |publisher =University of North Carolina - Greensboro|origyear=on microfilm 1977|via =University Microfilms, Ann Arbor, Michigan |year =1976|pages= 1\u2013319}}</ref><ref>Archives of the [[Association for Intercollegiate Athletics for Women]] (AIAW), Special Collections, [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] Libraries</ref> and six Big Ten Championships in 1988, 1989, 1992, 1995, 2005 and 2007.\n\n=== Volleyball ===\n{{main|Illinois Fighting Illini women's volleyball}}\nWomen's volleyball started in 1974.,<ref name=\"2012IlliniMediaGuide\">{{cite book |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/ill/sports/w-volley/auto_pdf/2012-13/misc_non_event/history-rec-book.pdf |title=2012 Illinois Volleyball Record Book |publisher=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign| location=Champaign, IL |year=2012 |pages=68 |accessdate=December 14, 2013}}</ref> Since moving into [[Huff Hall]] from the [[Kenney Gym and Kenney Gym Annex|Kenney Gym]] in 1990, the Illinois Volleyball team has remained in the top 10 in the nation for average home attendance. In 2013, the program broke its previous home attendance record, averaging 3,117 per match.<ref name=\"2013SeasonRecap\">{{cite news |url=http://www.fightingillini.com/sports/w-volley/recaps/121313aaf.html |title=Illinois' Most Well-Attended Season Ends at the Hand of Big Ten Foe |publisher=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign |location=Champaign, IL |year=2013 |accessdate=December 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214220002/http://www.fightingillini.com/sports/w-volley/recaps/121313aaf.html |archive-date=December 14, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Kenney Gym and Kenney Gym Annex|Kenney Gym]] served as the initial home court from 1974 through the 1989 season. Since the founding of the volleyball program in 1974, the Fighting Illini have had 30+ winning seasons.\n\n=== Wrestling ===\nThe current head coach of the University of Illinois Fighting Illini Wrestling team is Jim Heffernan, who started his tenth season in 2018. [[Huff Hall]] is the current home arena seating approximately 4,500.<ref>{{cite web |title=2013\u20132014 Wrestling Quick Facts |url=http://www.fightingillini.com/sports/m-wrestl/mtt/ill-m-wrestl-mtt.html |publisher=University of Illinois Athletics |accessdate=March 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330061451/http://www.fightingillini.com/sports/m-wrestl/mtt/ill-m-wrestl-mtt.html |archive-date=March 30, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* ''Big Ten Champions'': 1913, 1917, 1920, 1921, 1922, 1924, 1925, 1926, 1927, 1928, 1930, 1932, 1935, 1937, 1946, 1947, 1952, 2005\n* The University of Illinois has had 24 NCAA National Champions with the most recent being Jesse Delgado in 2013 and 2014 and Isaiah Martinez in 2015 and 2016.\n\n<timeline>\nDateFormat = yyyy\nImageSize  = width:900 height:auto barincrement:25\nPeriod     = from:1867 till:2015\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal\nPlotArea   = right:30 left:0 bottom:50 top:5\n\nColors = id:barcolor value:rgb(0.99,0.7,0.7)\n         id:line     value:black\n         id:bg       value:white\n\nPlotData=\n  width:15 textcolor:black shift:(5,-5) anchor:from fontsize:s\n\n  bar:1  color:skyblue from:1879 till:1881 text:Baseball (1879\u20131881, 1883\u2013present)\n  bar:1  color:white   from:1882 till:1883 text:\n  bar:1  color:skyblue from:1883 till:end  text:\n  bar:2  color:skyblue from:1890 till:end  text:Football (1890\u2013present)\n  bar:3  color:skyblue from:1890 till:end  text:Men's tennis (1890\u2013present)\n  bar:4  color:skyblue from:1901 till:end  text:Men's track