{"title_page": "Dinxperlo", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=May 2008}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|image_skyline      = Kerkje de Rietstap.jpg\n|image_caption      = Church \"De Rietstap\": the smallest church in the Netherlands\n|image_map          = Locator map of Dinxperlo.png\n|map_caption        = Location of the former municipality of Dinxperlo in the Netherlands\n|name               = Dinxperlo\n|subdivision_type   = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name   = [[Netherlands]]\n|subdivision_type1  = Province\n|subdivision_name1  = [[Gelderland]]\n|subdivision_type2  = Municipality\n|subdivision_name2  = [[Aalten]]\n|area-km2           =\n|population         = 7,442\n|population_as_of   = 1 January 2011\n|density            =\n|website            =\n|image_shield =Coat of arms of Dinxperlo.svg\n|image_flag =Dinxperlo vlag.svg\n|coordinates        = {{coord|51|51|45|N|6|29|14|E|region:NL|display=inline}}\n}}\n\n'''Dinxperlo''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8d\u026a\u014bksp\u0259rlo\u02d0}}) is a town and former [[Municipalities of the Netherlands|municipality]] (7442 inhabitants)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aalten.nl/index.php?simaction=content&mediumid=1&pagid=185&fontsize=12|title=Aalten / InternetOud / login|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122234810/http://www.aalten.nl/index.php?simaction=content&mediumid=1&pagid=185&fontsize=12|archivedate=2011-11-22}}</ref> in the eastern [[Netherlands]] ([[Achterhoek]] region), situated directly at the [[Germany-Netherlands border]]. \n\nSince 1 January 2005, Dinxperlo has been part of the municipality of [[Aalten]]. Before 2005, Dinxperlo was a separate municipality, covering the town of Dinxperlo itself and the village of [[De Heurne]].\n\nThe name of the village probably is derived from ''dingspel'' ([[Thing (assembly)|justice court]] or area)<ref>cf. [[Thingspiele]]</ref> and ''loo'' (wood). A popular explanation is that in the Middle Ages there was a [[court]] in the woods here. Dinxperlo used to have a [[coat of arms]] depicting [[Lady Justice]].\n\n==Attractions==\nOne of the town's main attractions is the Netherlands' smallest [[Church (building)|church]] (Kerkje \"De Rietstap\"), another one is a [[border]] museum (''Grenslandmuseum'').\n\n==Transportation==\nThe nearest train stations are [[Aalten railway station]] and [[Terborg railway station]], with train service operated by [[Arriva]] every half-hour. Bus number 40 connects Dinxperlo to Terborg station and bus number 195 connects Dinxperlo to Aalten station. Both services start in the Willem van Oranjeplein. The service runs from [[Arnhem]] ([[Arnhem railway station]]) to [[Doetinchem]] and [[Winterswijk]] stopping at various places on the way.\n\n==Dutch-German border==\nOne street in Dinxperlo, ''Heelweg'', is partly German in the village of [[Suderwick]], [[Borken]]. The road itself lies in the Netherlands, but one side of the housing zone is in Germany (where it is called ''Hellweg'').<ref>{{cite web|title=Dinxperlo (NL) / Suderwick (D)|url=http://www.grenzen.150m.com/dinxperloGB.htm|website=grenzen.150m.com|accessdate=7 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010224931/http://www.grenzen.150m.com/dinxperloGB.htm|archivedate=10 October 2014}}</ref> The unique boundary line is delimited by a treaty between Germany and the Netherlands signed in April 1960, which resulted in the return of Suderwick to then West Germany on 1 August 1963 after the Netherlands [[Dutch annexation of German territory after the Second World War|annexed]] the village soon after the Second World War as part of claims for war reparations. \n\nThe treaty also provides for the access arrangements of those living in German territory but with only access via Heelweg which is Dutch territory.<ref>{{Citation | last = | first = | author-link = | last2 = | first2 = | author2-link = | title = Treaty Between The Kingdom Of The Netherlands And The Federal Republic Of Germany Concerning The Course Of The Common Frontier, The Boundary Waters, Real Property Situated Near The Frontier, Traffic Crossing The Frontier On Land And Via Inland Waters, And Other Frontier Questions | date = 8 April 1960 | url = https://treaties.un.org/doc/publication/unts/volume%20508/v508.pdf |format=PDF| accessdate = 25 October 2019}}</ref> The houses there belong to the small town of [[Suderwick]], which might be translated as \"southern area\". Also, Dinxperlo houses a shared Dutch-German [[police station]].\n\nBesides [[Dutch language|Dutch]] and [[German language|German]], at both sides of the border a common dialect is spoken, which is a variety of [[West Low German|Low Saxon]].\n\n== DinxperFM internet radio == \n\nDinxperFM is a non-profit internet radio station focused on Dinxperlo. It is active with music, local news and information. The channel is managed by the Dinxperlo Media Management Foundation. The audio stream of the station can be listened to via TuneIn, but also directly via the DinxperFM webpage. DinxperFM is also active on social media such as Facebook. More information about DinxperFM can be found on the website: https://www.dinxperfm.nl\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Dinxperlo (NL), Flaggenskulptur -- 2016 -- 2328.jpg|Dinxperlo, sculpture of flags\nImage:Dinxperlo, kerk foto10 2010-07-19 15.41.JPG|Dinxperlo, church\nImage:Dinxperlo, modern straatzicht foto4 2010-07-19 14.23.JPG|Dinxperlo, Heelweg (exactly at the border)\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.dinxperlo.nl }}\n*{{Kuyper|Dinxperlo|ge|dinxperlo}} Map of the former municipality, around 1868.\n\n{{Coord|51|52|N|6|29|E|region:NL_type:city|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Gelderland]]\n[[Category:Former municipalities of Gelderland]]\n[[Category:Aalten]]\n\n\n{{Gelderland-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=May 2008}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|image_skyline      = Kerkje de Rietstap.jpg\n|image_caption      = Church \"De Rietstap\": the smallest church in the Netherlands\n|image_map          = Locator map of Dinxperlo.png\n|map_caption        = Location of the former municipality of Dinxperlo in the Netherlands\n|name               = Dinxperlo\n|subdivision_type   = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name   = [[Netherlands]]\n|subdivision_type1  = Province\n|subdivision_name1  = [[Gelderland]]\n|subdivision_type2  = Municipality\n|subdivision_name2  = [[Aalten]]\n|area-km2           =\n|population         = 7,442\n|population_as_of   = 1 January 2011\n|density            =\n|website            =\n|image_shield =Coat of arms of Dinxperlo.svg\n|image_flag =Dinxperlo vlag.svg\n|coordinates        = {{coord|51|51|45|N|6|29|14|E|region:NL|display=inline}}\n}}\n\n'''Dinxperlo''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8d\u026a\u014bksp\u0259rlo\u02d0}}) is a town and former [[Municipalities of the Netherlands|municipality]] (7442 inhabitants)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aalten.nl/index.php?simaction=content&mediumid=1&pagid=185&fontsize=12|title=Aalten / InternetOud / login|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122234810/http://www.aalten.nl/index.php?simaction=content&mediumid=1&pagid=185&fontsize=12|archivedate=2011-11-22}}</ref> in the eastern [[Netherlands]] ([[Achterhoek]] region), situated directly at the [[Germany-Netherlands border]]. \n\nSince 1 January 2005, Dinxperlo has been part of the municipality of [[Aalten]]. Before 2005, Dinxperlo was a separate municipality, covering the town of Dinxperlo itself and the village of [[De Heurne]].\n\nThe name of the village probably is derived from ''dingspel'' ([[Thing (assembly)|justice court]] or area)<ref>cf. [[Thingspiele]]</ref> and ''loo'' (wood). A popular explanation is that in the Middle Ages there was a [[court]] in the woods here. Dinxperlo used to have a [[coat of arms]] depicting [[Lady Justice]].\n\n==Attractions==\nOne of the town's main attractions is the Netherlands' smallest [[Church (building)|church]] (Kerkje \"De Rietstap\"), another one is a [[border]] museum (''Grenslandmuseum'').\n\n==Transportation==\nThe nearest train stations are [[Aalten railway station]] and [[Terborg railway station]], with train service operated by [[Arriva]] every half-hour. Bus number 40 connects Dinxperlo to Terborg station and bus number 195 connects Dinxperlo to Aalten station. Both services start in the Willem van Oranjeplein. The service runs from [[Arnhem]] ([[Arnhem railway station]]) to [[Doetinchem]] and [[Winterswijk]] stopping at various places on the way.\n\n==Dutch-German border==\nOne street in Dinxperlo, ''Heelweg'', is partly German in the village of [[Suderwick]], [[Borken]]. The road itself lies in the Netherlands, but one side of the housing zone is in Germany (where it is called ''Hellweg'').<ref>{{cite web|title=Dinxperlo (NL) / Suderwick (D)|url=http://www.grenzen.150m.com/dinxperloGB.htm|website=grenzen.150m.com|accessdate=7 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010224931/http://www.grenzen.150m.com/dinxperloGB.htm|archivedate=10 October 2014}}</ref> The unique boundary line is delimited by a treaty between Germany and the Netherlands signed in April 1960, which resulted in the return of Suderwick to then West Germany on 1 August 1963 after the Netherlands [[Dutch annexation of German territory after the Second World War|annexed]] the village soon after the Second World War as part of claims for war reparations. The treaty also provides for the access arrangements of those living in German territory but with only access via Heelweg which is Dutch territory.<ref>{{Citation | last = | first = | author-link = | last2 = | first2 = | author2-link = | title = Treaty Between The Kingdom Of The Netherlands And The Federal Republic Of Germany Concerning The Course Of The Common Frontier, The Boundary Waters, Real Property Situated Near The Frontier, Traffic Crossing The Frontier On Land And Via Inland Waters, And Other Frontier Questions | date = 8 April 1960 | url = https://treaties.un.org/doc/publication/unts/volume%20508/v508.pdf |format=PDF| accessdate = 25 October 2019}}</ref> The houses there belong to the small town of [[Suderwick]], which might be translated as \"southern area\". Also, Dinxperlo houses a shared Dutch-German [[police station]].\n\nBesides [[Dutch language|Dutch]] and [[German language|German]], at both sides of the border a common dialect is spoken, which is a variety of [[West Low German|Low Saxon]].\n\n== DinxperFM internet radio == \n\nDinxperFM is a non-profit internet radio station focused on Dinxperlo. It is active with music, local news and information. The channel is managed by the Dinxperlo Media Management Foundation. The audio stream of the station can be listened to via TuneIn, but also directly via the DinxperFM webpage. DinxperFM is also active on social media such as Facebook. More information about DinxperFM can be found on the website: https://www.dinxperfm.nl\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Dinxperlo (NL), Flaggenskulptur -- 2016 -- 2328.jpg|Dinxperlo, sculpture of flags\nImage:Dinxperlo, kerk foto10 2010-07-19 15.41.JPG|Dinxperlo, church\nImage:Dinxperlo, modern straatzicht foto4 2010-07-19 14.23.JPG|Dinxperlo, Heelweg (exactly at the border)\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.dinxperlo.nl }}\n*{{Kuyper|Dinxperlo|ge|dinxperlo}} Map of the former municipality, around 1868.\n\n{{Coord|51|52|N|6|29|E|region:NL_type:city|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Gelderland]]\n[[Category:Former municipalities of Gelderland]]\n[[Category:Aalten]]\n\n\n{{Gelderland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Slleong", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDutch-German border", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dinxperlo"}
